It is the second-brightest natural object in the night sky after the <a href=\"/wiki/Moon\">Moon</a>, reaching an <a href=\"/wiki/Apparent_magnitude\">apparent magnitude</a> of −4.6, bright enough to cast shadows.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-15\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 14;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[14]</span></a></span> Because Venus is an <a href=\"/wiki/Inferior_and_superior_planets\">inferior planet</a> from Earth, it never appears to venture far from the Sun; its <a href=\"/wiki/Elongation_(astronomy)\">elongation</a> reaches a maximum of 47.8°.</p></span><div class=\"hatnote\">This article is about the planet. 05-23 18:37:26.076 debug OkHttp " list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"mw-references\" data-mw-group=\"note\"><li id=\"cite_note-8\"> <span class=\"mw-reference-text\">Defining the rotation as retrograde, as done by NASA space missions and the USGS, puts <a href=\"/wiki/Ishtar_Terra\">Ishtar Terra</a> in the northern hemisphere and makes the axial tilt 2.64°. Following the <a href=\"/wiki/Right-hand_rule\">right-hand rule</a> for prograde rotation puts Ishtar Terra in the southern hemisphere and makes the axial tilt 177.36°.</span></li></ol></div></td></tr></tbody></table>\n\n\n\n<p>Venus is a <a href=\"/wiki/Terrestrial_planet\">terrestrial planet</a> and is sometimes called Earth's \"sister planet\" because of their similar size, mass, proximity to the Sun, and bulk composition. It is radically different from Earth in other respects. It has the densest <a href=\"/wiki/Atmosphere\">atmosphere</a> of the four terrestrial planets, consisting of more than 96% <a href=\"/wiki/Carbon_dioxide\">carbon dioxide</a>. The <a href=\"/wiki/Atmospheric_pressure\">atmospheric pressure</a> at the planet's surface is 92 times that of Earth. Venus is by far the hottest planet in the Solar System, with a mean surface temperature of <span>735</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>K (462</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>°C; 863</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>°F)</span>, even though <a href=\"/wiki/Mercury_(planet)\">Mercury</a> is closer to the Sun. Venus is shrouded by an opaque layer of highly reflective clouds of <a href=\"/wiki/Sulfuric_acid\">sulfuric acid</a>, preventing its surface from being seen from space in <a href=\"/wiki/Visible_light\">visible light</a>. It may have had water oceans in the past,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-16\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 15;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[15]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-17\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 16;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[16]</span></a></span> but these would have vaporised as the temperature rose due to a <a href=\"/wiki/Runaway_greenhouse_effect\">runaway greenhouse effect</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Jakosky-18\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 17;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[17]</span></a></span> The water has probably <a href=\"/wiki/Photodissociation\">photodissociated</a>, and the free hydrogen has been <a href=\"/wiki/Atmospheric_escape\">swept into interplanetary space</a> by the <a href=\"/wiki/Solar_wind\">solar wind</a> because of the lack of a <a href=\"/wiki/Magnetosphere\">planetary magnetic field</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-solarwind-19\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 18;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[18]</span></a></span> Venus's surface is a dry desertscape interspersed with slab-like rocks and periodically resurfaced by <a href=\"/wiki/Volcanology_of_Venus\">volcanism</a>.</p>\n\n<p>As one of the brightest objects in the sky, Venus has been a major fixture in human culture for as long as records have existed. It has been made sacred to gods of many cultures, and has been a prime inspiration for writers and poets as the \"morning star\" and \"evening star\". Venus was the first planet to have its motions plotted across the sky, as early as the second millennium BC,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-practice-20\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 19;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[19]</span></a></span> and was a prime target for early interplanetary exploration as the closest planet to Earth. It was the first planet beyond Earth visited by a spacecraft (<a href=\"/wiki/Mariner_2\">Mariner 2</a>) in 1962, and the first to be successfully landed on (by <a href=\"/wiki/Venera_7\">Venera 7</a>) in 1970. Venus's thick clouds render observation of its surface impossible in visible light, and the first detailed maps did not emerge until the arrival of the <a href=\"/wiki/Magellan_(spacecraft)\">Magellan orbiter</a> in 1991. Plans have been proposed for <a href=\"/wiki/Rover_(
05-23 18:37:26.076 debug OkHttp space_exploration)\">rovers</a> or more complex missions, but they are hindered by Venus's hostile surface conditions.</p>\n\n"},{"id":1,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Physical_characteristics","line":"Physical characteristics"},{"id":2,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Geography","line":"Geography"},{"id":3,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Surface_geology","line":"Surface geology"},{"id":4,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Internal_structure","line":"Internal structure"},{"id":5,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Atmosphere_and_climate","line":"Atmosphere and climate"},{"id":6,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Magnetic_field_and_core","line":"Magnetic field and core"},{"id":7,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Orbit_and_rotation","line":"Orbit and rotation"},{"id":8,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Observation","line":"Observation"},{"id":9,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Transits","line":"Transits"},{"id":10,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Pentagram_of_Venus","line":"Pentagram of Venus"},{"id":11,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Ashen_light","line":"Ashen light"},{"id":12,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Studies","line":"Studies"},{"id":13,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Early_studies","line":"Early studies"},{"id":14,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Ground-based_research","line":"Ground-based research"},{"id":15,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Exploration","line":"Exploration"},{"id":16,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"In_culture","line":"In culture"},{"id":17,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Etymology","line":"Etymology"},{"id":18,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Symbol","line":"Symbol"},{"id":19,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"In_fiction","line":"In fiction"},{"id":20,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Colonisation_and_terraforming","line":"Colonisation and terraforming"},{"id":21,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"See_also","line":"See also"},{"id":22,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Notes","line":"Notes"},{"id":23,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"References","line":"References"},{"id":24,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"External_links","line":"External links"},{"id":25,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Cartographic_resources","line":"Cartographic resources"}]}

It is similar to Earth in size and mass, and is often described as Earth's \"sister\" or \"twin\".<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-21\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 20;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[20]</span></a></span> The diameter of Venus is 12,092<span>&nbsp;</span>km (only 650<span>&nbsp;</span>km less than Earth's) and its mass is 81.5% of Earth's. Conditions on the Venusian surface differ radically from those on Earth because of its dense <a href=\"/wiki/Carbon_dioxide\">carbon dioxide</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Atmosphere\">atmosphere</a>. The mass of the atmosphere of Venus is 96.5% carbon dioxide, with most of the remaining 3.5% being <a href=\"/wiki/Nitrogen\">nitrogen</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-22\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 21;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[21]</span></a></span></p>\n\n","toclevel":1,"line":"Physical characteristics","anchor":"Physical_characteristics"},{"id":2,"text":"\n<p>The Venusian surface was a subject of speculation until some of its secrets were revealed by <a href=\"/wiki/Planetary_science\">planetary science</a> in the 20th century. <a href=\"/wiki/Venera\">Venera</a> landers in 1975 and 1982 returned images of a surface covered in sediment and relatively angular rocks.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-23\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 22;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[22]</span></a></span> The surface was mapped in detail by <a href=\"/wiki/Magellan_(spacecraft)\"><i>Magellan</i></a> in 1990–91. The ground shows evidence of extensive <a href=\"/wiki/Volcanology_of_Venus\">volcanism</a>, and the <a href=\"/wiki/Sulfur\">sulfur</a> in the atmosphere may indicate that there have been some recent eruptions.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-24\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 23;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[23]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-25\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 24;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[24]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>About 80% of the Venusian surface is covered by smooth, volcanic plains, consisting of 70% plains with wrinkle ridges and 10% smooth or lobate plains.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-26\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 25;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[25]</span></a></span> Two <a href=\"/wiki/Highland_continent\">highland \"continents\"</a> make up the rest of its surface area, one lying in the planet's northern hemisphere and the other just south of the equator. The northern continent is called <a href=\"/wiki/Ishtar_Terra\">Ishtar Terra</a>, after <a href=\"/wiki/Ishtar\">Ishtar</a> the <a href=\"/wiki/Babylon\">Babylonian</a> goddess of love, and is about the size of Australia. <a href=\"/wiki/Maxwell_Montes\">Maxwell Montes</a>, the highest mountain on Venus, lies on Ishtar Terra. Its peak is 11<span>&nbsp;</span>km above the Venusian average surface elevation. The southern continent is called <a href=\"/wiki/Aphrodite_Terra\">Aphrodite Terra</a>, after the <a href=\"/wiki/Greek_mythology\">Greek</a> goddess of love, and is the larger of the two highland regions at roughly the size of
05-23 18:37:26.196 debug OkHttp South America. A network of fractures and faults covers much of this area.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Kaufmann-27\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 26;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[26]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>The absence of evidence of <a href=\"/wiki/Lava\">lava</a> flow accompanying any of the visible <a href=\"/wiki/Caldera\">caldera</a> remains an enigma. The planet has few <a href=\"/wiki/Impact_crater\">impact craters</a>, demonstrating that the surface is relatively young, approximately 300–600 million years old.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Nimmo98-28\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 27;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[27]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Strom1994-29\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 28;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[28]</span></a></span> Venus has some unique surface features in addition to the impact craters, mountains, and valleys commonly found on rocky planets. Among these are flat-topped volcanic features called \"<a href=\"/wiki/Farra_(Venus)\">farra</a>\", which look somewhat like pancakes and range in size from 20 to 50<span>&nbsp;</span>km across, and from 100 to 1,000<span>&nbsp;</span>m high; radial, star-like fracture systems called \"novae\"; features with both radial and concentric fractures resembling spider webs, known as \"<a href=\"/wiki/Arachnoid_(astrogeology)\">arachnoids</a>\"; and \"coronae\", circular rings of fractures sometimes surrounded by a depression. These features are volcanic in origin.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Frankel-30\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 29;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[29]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Most Venusian surface features are named after historical and mythological women.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-31\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 30;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[30]</span></a></span> Exceptions are Maxwell Montes, named after <a href=\"/wiki/James_Clerk_Maxwell\">James Clerk Maxwell</a>, and highland regions <a href=\"/wiki/Alpha_Regio\">Alpha Regio</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Beta_Regio\">Beta Regio</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Ovda_Regio\">Ovda Regio</a>. The latter three features were named before the current system was adopted by the <a href=\"/wiki/International_Astronomical_Union\">International Astronomical Union</a>, the body which oversees <a href=\"/wiki/Planetary_nomenclature\">planetary nomenclature</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-jpl-magellan-32\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 31;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[31]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>The longitudes of physical features on Venus are expressed relative to its <a href=\"/wiki/Prime_meridian\">prime meridian</a>. The original prime meridian passed through the radar-bright spot at the centre of the oval feature Eve, located south of Alpha Regio.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Davies_1994-33\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 32;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[32]</span></a></span> After the Venera missions were completed, the prime meridian was redefined to pass through the central peak in the crater Ariadne.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-34\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 33;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[33]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-jpl-magellan2-35\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 34;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[34]</span></a></span></p>\n\n","toclevel":2,"line":"Geography","anchor":"Geography"},{"id":3,"text":"\n<div class=\"hatnote relarticle mainarticle\">Main articles: <a href=\"/wiki/Geology_of_Venus\">Geology of Venus</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Volcanology_of_Venus\">Volcanology of Venus</a></div>\n<figure class=\"mw-default-size\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Maat_Mons_on_Venus.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/16/Maat_Mons_on_Venus.jpg/220px-Maat_Mons_on_Venus.jpg\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/16/Maa

Venus has several times as many volcanoes as Earth, and it has 167 large volcanoes that are over 100<span>&nbsp;</span>km across. The only volcanic complex of this size on Earth is the <a href=\"/wiki/Hawaii_(island)\">Big Island</a> of Hawaii.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Frankel-30\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 29;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[29]</span></a></span><sup class=\"reference\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\" about=\"#mwt105\" typeof=\"mw:Transclusion\" data-mw=\"{&quot;parts&quot;:[{&quot;template&quot;:{&quot;target&quot;:{&quot;wt&quot;:&quot;rp&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:&quot;./Template:Rp&quot;},&quot;params&quot;:{&quot;1&quot;:{&quot;wt&quot;:&quot;154&quot;}},&quot;i&quot;:0}}]}\" id=\"mwZg\">:154</sup> This is not because Venus is more volcanically active than Earth, but because its crust is older. Earth's <a href=\"/wiki/Oceanic_crust\">oceanic crust</a> is continually recycled by <a href=\"/wiki/Subduction\">subduction</a> at the boundaries of <a href=\"/wiki/Tectonic_plate\">tectonic plates</a>, and has an average age of about 100 million years,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-36\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 35;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[35]</span></a></span> whereas the Venusian surface is estimated to be 300–600 million years old.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Nimmo98-28\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 27;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[27]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Frankel-30\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 29;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[29]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Several lines of evidence point to ongoing <a href=\"/wiki/Volcano\">volcanic</a> activity on Venus. During the Soviet <a href=\"/wiki/Venera_programme\">Venera programme</a>, the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Venera_9\">Venera 9</a></i> orbiter obtained spectroscopic evidence of <a href=\"/wiki/Lightning\">lightning</a> on Venus,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-37\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 36;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[36]</span></a></span> and the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Venera_12\">Venera 12</a></i> descent probe obtained additional evidence of lightning and <a href=\"/wiki/Thunder\">thunder</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Russell.2C_Philips-38\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 37;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[37]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-39\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 38;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[38]</span></a></span> The <a href=\"/wiki/European_Space_Agency\">European Space Agency</a>'s <i><a href=\"/wiki/Venus_Express\">Venus Express</a></i> in 2007 detected <a href=\"/wiki/Whistler_(radio)\">whistler waves</a> further confirming the occurrence of lightning on Venus.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Russell_2007-40\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 39;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[39]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Venus_Express-41\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 40;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[40]</span></a></span> Although rainfall drives <a href=\"/wiki/Thunderstorm\">thunderstorms</a> on Earth, there is no rainfall on the surface of Venus (though <a href=\"/wiki/Sulfuric_acid\">sulfuric acid</a> rain falls in the upper atmosphere, then evaporates around 25<span>&nbsp;</span>km above the surface). One possibility is that ash from a volcanic eruption was generating the lightning. Another piece of evidence comes from measurements of <a href=\"/wiki/Sulfur_dioxide\">sulfur dioxi
05-23 18:37:26.196 debug OkHttp de</a> concentrations in the atmosphere, which dropped by a factor of 10 between 1978 and 1986, jumped in 2006, and again declined 10-fold.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ESA_2012-12-03-42\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 41;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[41]</span></a></span> This may mean that levels had been boosted several times by large volcanic eruptions.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-43\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 42;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[42]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Marcq2012-44\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 43;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[43]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>In 2008 and 2009, the first direct evidence for ongoing volcanism was observed by <i>Venus Express</i>, in the form of four transient localised infrared hot spots within the rift zone <a href=\"/wiki/Ganiki_Chasma\">Ganis Chasma</a>,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-USGS_Ganis_Chasma-45\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 44;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[44]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-46\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 1;\" data-mw-group=\"n\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[n 1]</span></a></span> near the shield volcano <a href=\"/wiki/Maat_Mons\">Maat Mons</a>. Three of the spots were observed in more than one successive orbit. These spots are thought to represent lava freshly released by volcanic eruptions.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Lakdawalla2015-47\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 45;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[45]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ESA_2015-06-18-48\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 46;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[46]</span></a></span> The actual temperatures are not known, because the size of the hot spots could not be measured, but are likely have been in the 800–1100 K range, relative to a normal temperature of 740 K.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Shalygin2015-49\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 47;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[47]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<figure class=\"mw-default-size\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Mgn_p39146.png\" class=\"image\"><img src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bb/Mgn_p39146.png/220px-Mgn_p39146.png\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bb/Mgn_p39146.png/440px-Mgn_p39146.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bb/Mgn_p39146.png/330px-Mgn_p39146.png 1.5x\" height=\"174\" width=\"220\"></a><figcaption><a href=\"/wiki/Impact_crater\" class=\"image\">Impact craters</a> on the surface of Venus (false-colour image reconstructed from radar data)</figcaption></figure>\n\n<p>Almost a thousand impact craters on Venus are evenly distributed across its surface. On other cratered bodies, such as Earth and the Moon, craters show a range of states of degradation. On the Moon, degradation is caused by subsequent impacts, whereas on Earth it is caused by wind and rain erosion. On Venus, about 85% of the craters are in pristine condition. The number of craters, together with their well-preserved condition, indicates the planet underwent a global resurfacing event about 300–600 million years ago,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Nimmo98-28\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 27;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[27]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Strom1994-29\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 28;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[28]</span></a></span> followed by a decay in volcanism.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-50\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 48;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[48]</span></a></span> Whereas Earth's crust is in continuous motion, Venus is thought to be unable to sustain such a process. Without plate tectonics to dissipate heat from its mantle, Venus instead undergoes a cyclical process in which mantle temperatures rise until they reach a critical level that weakens the crust. 05-23 18:37:31.527 debug OkHttp tyle=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 29;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[29]</span></a></span> Earth <a href=\"/wiki/Gravity\">gravitationally</a> interacts with other objects in space, especially the Sun and the <a href=\"/wiki/Moon\">Moon</a>. During one orbit around the Sun, Earth rotates about its own axis 366.26 times, creating 365.26 <a href=\"/wiki/Solar_time\">solar days</a> or one <a href=\"/wiki/Sidereal_year\">sidereal year</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-sidereal_solar-36\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 7;\" data-mw-group=\"n\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[n 7]</span></a></span> Earth's axis of rotation is tilted 23.4° away from the perpendicular of its <a href=\"/wiki/Orbital_plane_(astronomy)\">orbital plane</a>, producing seasonal variations on the planet's surface with a period of one <a href=\"/wiki/Tropical_year\">tropical year</a> (365.24 solar days).<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-yoder1995-37\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 30;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[30]</span></a></span> The Moon is Earth's only permanent <a href=\"/wiki/Natural_satellite\">natural satellite</a>. Its gravitational interaction with Earth causes ocean tides, stabilizes the orientation of Earth's rotational axis, and gradually slows Earth's rotational rate.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-aaa428_261-38\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 31;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[31]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Earth's <a href=\"/wiki/Lithosphere\">lithosphere</a> is divided into several rigid <a href=\"/wiki/Plate_tectonics\">tectonic plates</a> that migrate across the surface over periods of many millions of years. 71% of Earth's surface is covered with water,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-39\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 32;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[32]</span></a></span> with the remainder consisting of continents and islands that together have many lakes and other sources of water that contribute to the <a href=\"/wiki/Hydrosphere\">hydrosphere</a>. Earth's <a href=\"/wiki/Polar_regions_of_Earth\">polar regions</a> are mostly covered with ice, including the <a href=\"/wiki/Antarctic_ice_sheet\">Antarctic ice sheet</a> and the sea ice of the Arctic ice pack. Earth's interior remains active with a solid iron inner core, a liquid outer core that generates the magnetic field, and a convecting <a href=\"/wiki/Mantle_(geology)\">mantle</a> that drives plate tectonics.</p>\n\n<p>Within its first billion years,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-age_earth1-40\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 33;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[33]</span></a></span> life appeared in Earth's oceans and began to affect <a href=\"/wiki/Atmosphere_of_Earth\">its atmosphere</a> and surface, leading to the proliferation of <a href=\"/wiki/Aerobic_organism\">aerobic</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Anaerobic_organism\">anaerobic organisms</a>. Since then, the combination of Earth's distance from the Sun, its physical properties and <a href=\"/wiki/Geological_history_of_Earth\">its geological history</a> have allowed life to thrive and evolve. The earliest undisputed life on Earth arose at least 3.5 billion years ago. Earlier physical evidence of life includes <a href=\"/wiki/Biogenic\">biogenic</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Graphite\">graphite</a> in 3.7 billion-year-old <a href=\"/wiki/Metasediment\">metasedimentary rocks</a> discovered in southwestern <a href=\"/wiki/Greenland\">Greenland</a>, as well as \"remains of <a href=\"/wiki/Biotic_material\">biotic life</a>\" found in 4.1 billion-year-old rocks in <a href=\"/wiki/Western_Australia\">Western Australia</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-AP-20151019-41\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 34;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[34]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-PNAS-20151014-pdf-42\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 35;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[35]</span></a></span> Earth's <a href=\"/wiki/Biodiversity\">biodi

In <a href=\"/wiki/Nebular_theory\">nebular theory</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Planetesimal\">planetesimals</a> form by <a href=\"/wiki/Accretion_(astrophysics)\">accretion</a>. structure","anchor":"Internal_structure"},{"id":11,"text":"\n<div class=\"hatnote relarticle mainarticle\">Main article: <a href=\"/wiki/Earth's_internal_heat_budget\">Earth's internal heat budget</a></div>\n<p>Earth's <a href=\"/wiki/Internal_heat\">internal heat</a> comes from a combination of residual heat from <a href=\"/wiki/Planetary_accretion\">planetary accretion</a> (about 20%) and heat produced through <a href=\"/wiki/Radioactive_decay\">radioactive decay</a> (80%).<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-turcotte-129\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 113;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[113]</span></a></span> The major heat-producing <a href=\"/wiki/Isotope\">isotopes</a> within Earth are <a href=\"/wiki/Potassium\">potassium-40</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Uranium\">uranium-238</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Uranium-235\">uranium-235</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Thorium\">thorium-232</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-sanders20031210-130\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 114;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[114]</span></a></span> At the center, the temperature may be up to <span>6,000</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>°C (10,830</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>°F)</span>,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-131\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 115;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[115]</span></a></span> and the pressure could reach 360<span>&nbsp;</span><a href=\"/wiki/GPa\">GPa</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ptrsl360_1795_1227-132\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 116;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[116]</span></a></span> Because much of the heat is provided by radioactive decay, scientists postulate that early in Earth's history, before isotopes with short half-lives had been depleted, Earth's heat production would have been much higher. This extra heat production, twice present-day at approximately <span class=\"nowrap\"><span style=\"display:none\" class=\"sortkey\">7016946728000000000♠</span>3<span>&nbsp;</span><a href=\"/wiki/Year#SI_prefix_multipliers\">Ga</a></span>,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-turcotte-129\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 113;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[113]</span></a></span> would have increased temperature gradients with radius, increasing the rates of <a href=\"/wiki/Mantle_convection\">mantle convection</a> and plate tectonics, and allowing the production of uncommon igneous rocks such as <a href=\"/wiki/Komatiites\">komatiites</a> that are rarely formed today.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-epsl121_1-133\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 117;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[117]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<table class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\">\n<caption id=\"mwAdc\"> Present-day major heat-producing isotopes<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-T.26S_137-134\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 118;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[118]</span></a></span></caption>\n<tbody id=\"mwAdg\"><tr id=\"mwAdk\">\n<th id=\"mwAdo\"> Isotope</th>\n<th id=\"mwAds\"> Heat release<br id=\"mwAdw\"><span style=\"font-size: smaller;\"><span class=\"sfrac nowrap\" style=\"display:inline-block; vertical-align:-0.5em; font-size:85%; text-align:center;\"><span style=\"display:block; line-height:1em; margin:0 0.1em;\">W</span><span class=\"visualhide\">/</s

Three-quarters of the atmosphere's mass is contained within the first 11<span>&nbsp;</span>km of the surface. This lowest layer is called the troposphere. Energy from the Sun heats this layer, and the surface below, causing expansion of the air. This lower-density air then rises, and is replaced by cooler, higher-density air. The result is <a href=\"/wiki/Atmospheric_circulation\">atmospheric circulation</a> that drives the weather and climate through redistribution of thermal energy.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-moran2005-172\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 154;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[154]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>The primary atmospheric circulation bands consist of the <a href=\"/wiki/Trade_winds\">trade winds</a> in the equatorial region below 30° latitude and the <a href=\"/wiki/Westerlies\">westerlies</a> in the mid-latitudes between 30° and 60°.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-berger2002-173\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 155;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[155]</span></a></span> <a href=\"/wiki/Ocean_current\">Ocean currents</a> are also important factors in determining climate, particularly the <a href=\"/wiki/Thermohaline_circulation\">thermohaline circulation</a> that distributes thermal energy from the equatorial oceans to the polar regions.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-rahmstorf2003-174\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 156;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[156]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Water vapor generated through surface evaporation is transported by circulatory patterns in the atmosphere. When atmospheric conditions permit an uplift of warm, humid air, this water condenses and falls to the surface as precipitation.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-moran2005-172\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 154;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[154]</span></a></span> Most of the water is then transported to lower elevations by river systems and usually returned to the oceans or deposited into lakes. This <a href=\"/wiki/Water_cycle\">water cycle</a> is a vital mechanism for supporting life on land, and is a primary factor in the erosion of surface features over geological periods. Precipitation patterns vary widely, ranging from several meters of water per year to less than a millimeter. Atmospheric circulation, topographic features and temperature differences determine the average precipitation that falls in each region.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-hydrologic_cycle-175\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 157;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[157]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>The amount of solar energy reaching Earth's surface decreases with increasing latitude. At higher latitudes the sunlight reaches the surface at lower angles and it must pass through thicker columns of the atmosphere. As a result, the mean annual air temperature at sea level decreases by about <span>0.4</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>°C (0.7</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>°F)</span> per degree of latitude from the equator.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-sadava_heller2006-176\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 158;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[158]</span></a></span> Earth's surface can be subdivided into specific latitudinal belts of approximately homogeneous climate. Ranging from the equator to the polar regions, these are the <a href=\"/wiki/Tropics\">tropical</a> (or equatorial), <a href=\"/wiki/Subtropics\">subtropical</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Temperate\">temperate</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Polar_region\">polar</a> climates.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-climate_zones-177\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 159;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[159]</span></a></span> Climate can also be classified based on the temperature and precipitation, with the climate regions characterized by fairly uniform air masses. Mars is the site of <a href=\"/wiki/Olympus_Mons\">Olympus Mons</a>, the largest <a href=\"/wiki/Volcano\">volcano</a> and second-highest known mountain in the Solar System, and of <a href=\"/wiki/Valles_Marineris\">Valles Marineris</a>, one of the largest canyons in the Solar System. The smooth <a href=\"/wiki/Borealis_basin\">Borealis basin</a> in the northern hemisphere covers 40% of the planet and may be a giant impact feature.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-northcratersn-17\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 16;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[16]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-northcraterguard-18\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 17;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[17]</span></a></span> Mars has two <a href=\"/wiki/Moons_of_Mars\">moons</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Phobos_(moon)\">Phobos</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Deimos_(moon)\">Deimos</a>, which are small and irregularly shaped. These may be captured <a href=\"/wiki/Asteroid\">asteroids</a>,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-19\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 18;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[18]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-adler-20\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 19;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[19]</span></a></span> similar to <a href=\"/wiki/5261_Eureka\">5261 Eureka</a>, a <a href=\"/wiki/Mars_trojan\">Mars trojan</a>.</p>\n\n<p>Until the first successful Mars flyby in 1965 by <i><a href=\"/wiki/Mariner_4\">Mariner 4</a></i>, many speculated about the presence of liquid water on the planet's surface. This was based on observed periodic variations in light and dark patches, particularly in the polar <a href=\"/wiki/Latitude\">latitudes</a>, which appeared to be seas and continents; long, dark <a href=\"/wiki/Striation_(geology)\">striations</a> were interpreted by some as irrigation channels for liquid water. These straight line features were later explained as <a href=\"/wiki/Optical_illusion\">optical illusions</a>, though geological evidence gathered by uncrewed missions suggests that Mars once had large-scale water coverage on its surface at some earlier stage of its existence.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-marswater-21\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 20;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[20]</span></a></span> In 2005, radar data revealed the presence of large quantities of water ice at the poles<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-specials1-22\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 21;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[21]</span></a></span> and at mid-latitudes.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-jsg.utexas.edu-23\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 22;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[22]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-esa050221-24\" style=\"counte

The <i><a href=\"/wiki/Phoenix_(spacecraft)\">Phoenix</a></i> lander directly sampled water ice in shallow Martian soil on July 31, 2008.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-spacecraft1-25\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 24;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[24]</span></a></span> On September 28, 2015, NASA announced the presence of briny flowing <a href=\"/wiki/Saline_water\">salt water</a> on the Martian surface.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-26\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 25;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[25]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Mars is host to seven functioning <a href=\"/wiki/Spacecraft\">spacecraft</a>: five in orbit—<i><a href=\"/wiki/2001_Mars_Odyssey\">2001 Mars Odyssey</a></i>, <i><a href=\"/wiki/Mars_Express\">Mars Express</a></i>, <i><a href=\"/wiki/Mars_Reconnaissance_Orbiter\">Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter</a></i>, <a href=\"/wiki/MAVEN\">MAVEN</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Mars_Orbiter_Mission\">Mars Orbiter Mission</a>—and two on the surface—<a href=\"/wiki/Mars_Exploration_Rover\">Mars Exploration Rover</a> <i><a href=\"/wiki/Opportunity_(rover)\">Opportunity</a></i> and the <a href=\"/wiki/Mars_Science_Laboratory\">Mars Science Laboratory</a> <i><a href=\"/wiki/Curiosity_(rover)\">Curiosity</a></i>. Observations by the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Mars_Reconnaissance_Orbiter\">Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter</a></i> have revealed possible flowing water during the warmest months on Mars.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NASA_.E2.80.93_NASA_Spacecraft_Data_Suggest_Water_Flowing_on_Mars-27\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 26;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[26]</span></a></span> In 2013, NASA's <i>Curiosity</i> rover discovered that Mars's soil contains between 1.5% and 3% water by mass (albeit attached to other compounds and thus not freely accessible).<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Guardian-28\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 27;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[27]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>There are ongoing investigations assessing the past <a href=\"/wiki/Planetary_habitability\">habitability</a> potential of Mars, as well as <a href=\"/wiki/Life_on_Mars\">the possibility of extant life</a>. <i>In situ</i> investigations have been performed by the <a href=\"/wiki/Viking_program#Viking_landers\"><i>Viking</i> landers</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Spirit_(rover)\"><i>Spirit</i></a> and <i>Opportunity</i> rovers, <a href=\"/wiki/Phoenix_(spacecraft)\"><i>Phoenix</i></a> lander, and <i>Curiosity</i> rover. Future astrobiology missions are planned, including the <a href=\"/wiki/Mars_2020\">Mars 2020</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/ExoMars_rover\">ExoMars</a> rovers.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-curiosity_search_for_life-29\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 28;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[28]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MER_Search_for_Life-30\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 29;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[29]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ExoMars's_search_for_life-31\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 30;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[30]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Mars_2020_search_for_life-32\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 31;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[31]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Mars can easily be seen from Earth with the naked eye, as can its reddish coloring. The surface of Mars is primarily composed of <a href=\"/wiki/Tholeiitic_magma_series\">tholeiitic</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Basalt\">basalt</a>,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-science324_5928_736-39\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 38;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[38]</span></a></span> although parts are more <a href=\"/wiki/Silica\">silica</a>-rich than typical basalt and may be similar to <a href=\"/wiki/Andesitic\">andesitic</a> rocks on Earth or silica glass. Regions of low <a href=\"/wiki/Albedo\">albedo</a> show concentrations of <a href=\"/wiki/Plagioclase_feldspar\">plagioclase feldspar</a>, with northern low albedo regions displaying higher than normal concentrations of sheet silicates and high-silicon glass. Parts of the southern highlands include detectable amounts of high-calcium <a href=\"/wiki/Pyroxenes\">pyroxenes</a>. Localized concentrations of <a href=\"/wiki/Hematite\">hematite</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Olivine\">olivine</a> have also been found.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-jgr107_E6-40\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 39;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[39]</span></a></span> Much of the surface is deeply covered by finely grained <a href=\"/wiki/Iron(III)_oxide\">iron(III) oxide</a> dust.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-sci300a-41\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 40;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[40]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-sci300b-42\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 41;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[41]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<figure class=\"mw-default-size mw-halign-left\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:USGS-MarsMap-sim3292-20140714-crop.png\" class=\"im

This <a href=\"/wiki/Paleomagnetism\">paleomagnetism</a> of magnetically susceptible minerals has properties that are similar to the <a href=\"/wiki/Magnetic_striping\">alternating bands found on the ocean floors of Earth</a>. One theory, published in 1999 and re-examined in October 2005 (with the help of the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Mars_Global_Surveyor\">Mars Global Surveyor</a></i>), is that these bands demonstrate <a href=\"/wiki/Plate_tectonics\">plate tectonics</a> on Mars four <a href=\"/wiki/1000000000_(number)\">billion</a> years ago, before the planetary <a href=\"/wiki/Dynamo_theory\">dynamo</a> ceased to function and the planet's magnetic field faded away.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-plates-45\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 44;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[44]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>During the <a href=\"/wiki/Formation_and_evolution_of_the_Solar_System\">Solar System's formation</a>, Mars was created as the result of a <a href=\"/wiki/Stochastic_process\">stochastic process</a> of run-away accretion out of the <a href=\"/wiki/Protoplanetary_disk\">protoplanetary disk</a> that orbited the Sun. Mars has many distinctive chemical features caused by its position in the Solar System. Elements with comparatively low boiling points, such as <a href=\"/wiki/Chlorine\">chlorine</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Phosphorus\">phosphorus</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Sulphur\">sulphur</a>, are much more common on Mars than Earth; these elements were probably removed from areas closer to the Sun by the young star's energetic <a href=\"/wiki/Solar_wind\">solar wind</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ssr96_1_4_197-46\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 45;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[45]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>After the formation of the planets, all were subjected to the so-called \"<a href=\"/wiki/Late_Heavy_Bombardment\">Late Heavy Bombardment</a>\". About 60% of the surface of Mars shows a record of impacts from that era,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-zharkov93-47\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 46;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[46]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-icarus165_1-48\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 47;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[47]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-barlow88-49\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 48;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[48]</span></a></span> whereas much of the remaining surface is probably underlain by immense impact basins caused by those events. It is a <a href=\"/wiki/Giant_planet\">giant planet</a> with a <a href=\"/wiki/Mass\">mass</a> one-thousandth that of the Sun, but two and a half times that of all the other planets in the Solar System combined. Jupiter is a <a href=\"/wiki/Gas_giant\">gas giant</a>, along with <a href=\"/wiki/Saturn\">Saturn</a>. (<a href=\"/wiki/Uranus\">Uranus</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Neptune\">Neptune</a> are <a href=\"/wiki/Ice_giant\">ice giants</a>.) Jupiter was known to <a href=\"/wiki/Astronomer\">astronomers</a> of ancient times.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-13\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 11;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[11]</span></a></span> The <a href=\"/wiki/Ancient_Rome\">Romans</a> named it after <a href=\"/wiki/Roman_mythology\">their god</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Jupiter_(mythology)\">Jupiter</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-14\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 12;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[12]</span></a></span> When viewed from <a href=\"/wiki/Earth\">Earth</a>, Jupiter can reach an <a href=\"/wiki/Apparent_magnitude\">apparent magnitude</a> of −2.94, bright enough for its reflected light to cast shadows,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-15\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 13;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[13]</span></a></span> and making it on average the third-brightest object in the <a href=\"/wiki/Night_sky\">night sky</a> after the <a href=\"/wiki/Moon\">Moon</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Venus\">Venus</a>.</p></span><div class=\"hatnote\">This article is about the planet. For the Roman god, see <a href=\"/wiki/Jupiter_(mythology)\">Jupiter (mythology)</a>. It may also have a rocky core of heavier elements,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-coreuncertainty-16\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 14;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[14]</span></a></span> but like the other giant planets, Jupiter lacks a well-defined solid surface. Because of its rapid rotation, the planet's shape is that of an <a href=\"/wiki/Oblate_spheroid\">oblate spheroid</a> (it has a slight but noticeable bulge around the equator). The outer atmosphere is visibly segregated into several bands at different latitudes, resulting in turbulence and storms along their interacting boundaries. A prominent result is the <a href=\"/wiki/Great_Red_Spot\">Great Red Spot</a>, a giant storm that is known to have existed since at least the 17th century when it was first seen by <a href=\"/wiki/Telescope\">telescope</a>. Surrounding Jupiter is a faint <a href=\"/wiki/Planetary_ring\">planetary ring</a> system and a powerful <a href=\"/wiki/Magnetosphere\">magnetosphere</a>. Jupiter has at least <a href=\"/wiki/Moons_of_Jupiter\">67 moons</a>, including the four large <a href=\"/wiki/Galilean_moons\">Galilean moons</a> discovered by <a href=\"/wiki/Galileo_Galilei\">Galileo Galilei</a> in 1610. <a href=\"/wiki/Ganymede_(moon)\">Ganymede</a>, the largest of these, has a diameter greater than that of the planet <a href=\"/wiki/Mercury_(planet)\">Mercury</a>.</p>\n\n<p>Jupiter has been explored on several occasions by <a href=\"/wiki/Robotic_spacecraft\">robotic spacecraft</a>, most notably during the early <i><a href=\"/wiki/Pioneer_program\">Pioneer</a></i> and <i><a href=\"/wiki/Voyager_program\">Voyager</a></i> <a href=\"/wiki/Planetary_flyby\">flyby</a> missions and later by the <a href=\"/wiki/Galileo_(spacecraft)\"><i>Galileo</i> orbiter</a>. Jupiter was most recently visited by a probe in late February 2007, when <i><a href=\"/wiki/New_Horizons\">New Horizons</a></i> <a href=\"/wiki/Gravitational_slingshot\">used Jupiter's gravity</a> to increase its speed and bend its trajectory en route to <a href=\"/wiki/Pluto\">Pluto</a>. The next probe to visit the planet will be <i><a href=\"/wiki/Juno_(spacecraft)\">Juno</a></i>, which is expected to arrive in July 2016. Future targets for exploration in the Jupiter system include the probable ice-covered liquid ocean of its moon <a href=\"/wiki/Europa_(moon)\">Europa</a>.</p>\n\n"},{"id":1,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Formation_and_migration","line":"Formation and migration"},{"id":2,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Structure","line":"Structure"},{"id":3,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Composition","line":"Composition"},{"id":4,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Mass_and_size","line":"Mass and size"},{"id":5,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Internal_structure","line":"Internal structure"},{"id":6,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Atmosphere","line":"Atmosphere"},{"id":7,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Cloud_layers","line":"Cloud layers"},{"id":8,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Great_Red_Spot_and_other_vortice

As Jupiter came toward the inner Solar System, in what theorists call the <a href=\"/wiki/Grand_Tack_Hypothesis\">Grand Tack Hypothesis</a>, gravitational tugs and pulls occurred causing a series of collisions between the super-Earths as their orbits began to overlap.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-17\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 15;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[15]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Astronomers have discovered nearly 500 planetary systems each with multiple planets, and typically these systems include a few planets with masses several times greater than Earth's (super-Earths), orbiting closer to their star than Mercury is to the Sun, and Jupiter-like gas giants are also often found close to their star.</p>\n\n<p>Jupiter moving out of the inner Solar System would have allowed the formation of inner planets, including <a href=\"/wiki/Earth\">Earth</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-18\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 16;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[16]</span></a></span></p>\n\n","toclevel":1,"line":"Formation and migration","anchor":"Formation_and_migration"},{"id":2,"text":"\n<p>Jupiter is composed primarily of gaseous and liquid matter. It is the largest of the four giant planets in the Solar System and hence its largest planet. It has a diameter of <span>142,984</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>km (88,846</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>mi)</span> at its <a href=\"/wiki/Equator\">equator</a>. The average density of Jupiter, 1.326<span>&nbsp;</span>g/cm<sup id=\"mwRw\">3</sup>, is the second highest of the giant planets, but lower than those of the four <a href=\"/wiki/Terrestrial_planet\">terrestrial planets</a>.</p>\n\n","toclevel":1,"line":"Structure","anchor":"Structure"},{"id":3,"text":"\n<p>Jupiter's upper atmosphere is composed of about 88–92% hydrogen and 8–12% helium by percent volume of gas <a href=\"/wiki/Molecule\">molecules</a>. A helium atom has about four times as much mass as a hydrogen atom, so the composition changes when described as the proportion of mass contributed by different atoms. Thus, <a href=\"/wiki/Atmosphere_of_Jupiter\">Jupiter's atmosphere</a> is approximately 75% hydrogen and 24% helium by mass, with the remaining one percent of the mass consisting of other elements. The interior contains denser materials, such that the distribution is roughly 71% hydrogen, 24% helium, and 5% other elements by mass. The atmosphere contains trace amounts of <a href=\"/wiki/Methane\">methane</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Water_vapor\">water vapor</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Ammonia\">ammonia</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Silicon\">silicon</a>-based compounds. The outermost layer of the atmosphere contains <a href=\"/wiki/Crystal\">crystals</a> of frozen ammonia.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-voyager-19\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 17;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[17]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-cassini-20\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 18;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[18]</span></a></span> Through <a href=\"/wiki/Infrared\">infrared</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Ultraviolet\">ultraviolet</a> measurements, trace amounts of <a href=\"/wiki/Benzene\">benzene</a> and other <

The core is often described as <a href=\"/wiki/Rock_(geology)\">rocky</a>, but its detailed composition is unknown, as are the properties of materials at the temperatures and pressures of those depths (see below). In 1997, the existence of the core was suggested by gravitational measurements,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-guillot04-35\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 33;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[33]</span></a></span> indicating a mass of from 12 to 45 times the Earth's mass or roughly 4%–14% of the total mass of Jupiter.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-elkins-tanton-34\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 32;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[32]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-37\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 35;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[35]</span></a></span>\nThe presence of a core during at least part of Jupiter's history is suggested by models of planetary formation that require the formation of a rocky or icy core massive enough to collect its bulk of hydrogen and helium from the <a href=\"/wiki/Nebular_hypothesis\">protosolar nebula</a>. Assuming it did exist, it may have shrunk as convection currents of hot liquid metallic hydrogen mixed with the molten core and carried its contents to higher levels in the planetary interior. A core may now be entirely absent, as gravitational measurements are not yet precise enough to rule that possibility out entirely.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-guillot04-35\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 33;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[33]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-38\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 36;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[36]</span></a></span></p>\n<figure class=\"mw-halign-right\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:PIA19640-Jupiter-Infrared-Animation-20150516.gif\" class=\"image\"><img src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e9/PIA19640-Jupiter-Infrared-Animation-20150516.gif/150px-PIA19640-Jupiter-Infrared-Animation-20150516.gif\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e9/PIA19640-Jupiter-Infrared-Animation-20150516.gif/300px-PIA19640-Jupiter-Infrared-Animation-20150516.gif 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e9/PIA19640-Jupiter-Infrared-Animation-20150516.gif/225px-PIA19640-Jupiter-Infrared-Animation-20150516.gif 1.5x\" height=\"152\" width=\"150\"></a><figcaption>Animation of Jupiter seen in infrared</figcaption></figure>\n\n<p>The uncertainty of the models is tied to the error margin in hitherto measured parameters: one of the rotational coefficients (J<sub id=\"mwmQ\">6</sub>) used to describe the planet's gravitational moment, Jupiter's equatorial radius, and its temperature at 1 bar pressure. The <a href=\"/wiki/Juno_(spacecraft)\">Juno mission</a>, which is scheduled to arrive in July 2016, is expected to further constrain the values of these parameters for better models of the core.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-39\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 37;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[37]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>The core region is surrounded by dense <a href=\"/wiki/Metallic_hydrogen\">metallic hydrogen</a>, which extends outward to about 78% of the radius of the planet.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-elkins-tanton-34\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 32;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[32]</span></a></span> Rain-like droplets of helium and neon precipitate downward through this layer, depleting the abundance of these elements in the upper atmosphere.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-galileo_ms-23\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 21;\"><span class=\"m

Since then, the large number of new small outer moons has complicated this picture. There are now thought to be six main groups, although some are more distinct than others.</p>\n\n<p>A basic sub-division is a grouping of the eight inner regular moons, which have nearly circular orbits near the plane of Jupiter's equator and are thought to have formed with Jupiter. The remainder of the moons consist of an unknown number of small irregular moons with elliptical and inclined orbits, which are thought to be captured asteroids or fragments of captured asteroids. Irregular moons that belong to a group share similar orbital elements and thus may have a common origin, perhaps as a larger moon or captured body that broke up.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a The orbits of most of the system's planets lie closer to Jupiter's <a href=\"/wiki/Orbital_plane_(astronomy)\">orbital plane</a> than the Sun's <a href=\"/wiki/Celestial_equator\">equatorial plane</a> (<a href=\"/wiki/Mercury_(planet)\">Mercury</a> is the only planet that is closer to the Sun's equator in orbital tilt), the <a href=\"/wiki/Kirkwood_gap\">Kirkwood gaps</a> in the <a href=\"/wiki/Asteroid_belt\">asteroid belt</a> are mostly caused by Jupiter, and the planet may have been responsible for the <a href=\"/wiki/Late_Heavy_Bombardment\">Late Heavy Bombardment</a> of the inner Solar System's history.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-121\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 119;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[119]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<figure class=\"mw-default-size\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:InnerSolarSystem-en.png\" class=\"image\"><img src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/InnerSolarSystem-en.png/220px-InnerSolarSystem-en.png\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/InnerSolarSystem-en.png/440px-InnerSolarSystem-en.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/InnerSolarSystem-en.png/330px-InnerSolarSystem-en.png 1.5x\" height=\"220\" width=\"220\"></a><figcaption>This diagram shows the <a href=\"/wiki/Trojan_(astronomy)\" class=\"image\">Trojan asteroids</a> in Jupiter's orbit, as well as the main <a href=\"/wiki/Asteroid_belt\" class=\"image\">asteroid belt</a>.</figcaption></figure>\n<p>Along with its moons, Jupiter's gravitational field controls numerous <a href=\"/wiki/Asteroid\">asteroids</a> that have settled into the regions of the <a href=\"/wiki/Lagrangian_point\">Lagrangian points</a> preceding and following Jupiter in its orbit around the Sun. These are known as the <a href=\"/wiki/Trojan_asteroid\">Trojan asteroids</a>, and are divided into <a href=\"/wiki/List_of_Trojan_asteroids_(Greek_camp)\">Greek</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/List_of_Trojan_asteroids_(Trojan_camp)\">Trojan</a> \"camps\" to commemorate the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Iliad\">Iliad</a></i>. The first of these, <a href=\"/wiki/588_Achilles\">588 Achilles</a>, was discovered by <a href=\"/wiki/Max_Wolf\">Max Wolf</a> in 1906; since then more than two thousand have been discovered.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-122\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 120;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[120]</span></a></span> The largest is <a href=\"/wiki/624_Hektor\">624 Hektor</a>.</p>\n\n<p>Most <a href=\"/wiki/List_of_periodic_comets\">short-period comets</a> belong to the Jupiter family—defined as comets with <a href=\"/wiki/Semi-major_axis\">semi-major axes</a> smaller than Jupiter's. Jupiter family comets are thought to form in the <a href=\"/wiki/Kuiper_belt\">Kuiper belt</a> outside the orbit of Neptune. This core is surrounded by a deep layer of <a href=\"/wiki/Metallic_hydrogen\">metallic hydrogen</a>, an intermediate layer of <a href=\"/wiki/Liquid_hydrogen\">liquid hydrogen</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Liquid_helium\">liquid helium</a>, and finally outside the <a href=\"/wiki/Frenkel_line\">Frenkel line</a> a gaseous outer layer.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Composition_ref-16\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 15;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[15]</span></a></span> Saturn has a pale yellow hue due to <a href=\"/wiki/Ammonia\">ammonia</a> crystals in its upper atmosphere. <a href=\"/wiki/Electrical_current\">Electrical current</a> within the metallic hydrogen layer is thought to give rise to Saturn's planetary <a href=\"/wiki/Magnetic_field\">magnetic field</a>, which is weaker than Earth's, but has a <a href=\"/wiki/Magnetic_moment\">magnetic moment</a> 580 times that of Earth due to Saturn's larger size. Saturn's magnetic field strength is around one-twentieth of Jupiter's.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-mag-17\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 16;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[16]</span></a></span> The outer <a href=\"/wiki/Atmosphere\">atmosphere</a> is generally bland and lacking in contrast, although long-lived features can appear. <a href=\"/wiki/Wind_speed\">Wind speeds</a> on Saturn can reach <span>1,800</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>km/h (500</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>m/s)</span>, higher than on Jupiter, but not as high as those on <a href=\"/wiki/Neptune\">Neptune</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Science_Ch._2004-18\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 17;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[17]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Saturn has a prominent <a href=\"/wiki/Rings_of_Saturn\">ring system</a> that consists of nine continuous main rings and three discontinuous arcs and that is composed mostly of ice particles with a smaller amount of rocky debris and <a href=\"/wiki/Cosmic_dust\">dust</a>. Sixty-two<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-19\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 18;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[18]</span></a></span> <a href=\"/wiki/Moons_of_Saturn\">moons</a> are known to orbit Saturn, of which fifty-three are officially named. This does not include the hundreds of <a href=\"/wiki/Moonlet\">moonlets</a> comprising the rings. <a href=\"/wiki/Titan_(moon)\">Titan</a>, Saturn's largest moon, and the second-largest in the Solar System, is larger than the planet <a href=\"/wiki/Mercury_(planet)\">Mercury</a>, although less massive, and is the only moon in the Solar System to have a substantial atmosphere.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Titan_ref-20\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 19;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[19]</span></a></span></p>\n<div class=\"toclimit-3\"><meta property=\"mw:PageProp/toc\"></div>\n\n"},{"id":1

It lacks a definite surface, though it may have a solid core.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-melosh2011-21\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 20;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[20]</span></a></span> Saturn's rotation causes it to have the shape of an <a href=\"/wiki/Oblate_spheroid\">oblate spheroid</a>; that is, it is flattened at the poles and bulges at its equator. Its equatorial and polar radii differ by almost 10%: 60,268<span>&nbsp;</span>km versus 54,364<span>&nbsp;</span>km, respectively.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-fact-4\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 4;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[4]</span></a></span> Jupiter, <a href=\"/wiki/Uranus\">Uranus</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Neptune\">Neptune</a>, the other giant planets in the Solar System, are also oblate but to a lesser extent. Saturn is the only planet of the Solar System that is less dense than water—about 30% less.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-preserve-22\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 21;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[21]</span></a></span> Although Saturn's <a href=\"/wiki/Planetary_core\">core</a> is considerably denser than water, the average <a href=\"/wiki/Relative_density\">specific density</a> of the planet is 0.69<span>&nbsp;</span>g/cm<sup id=\"mwOg\">3</sup> due to the atmosphere. The temperature, pressure, and density inside Saturn all rise steadily toward the core, which causes hydrogen to transition into a metal in the deeper layers.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ssr152_1_423-24\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 23;\"><span class=\"mw-
05-23 18:37:48.616 debug OkHttp reflink-text\">[23]</span></a></span></p>\n \n<p>Standard planetary models suggest that the interior of Saturn is similar to that of <a href=\"/wiki/Jupiter\">Jupiter</a>, having a small rocky core surrounded by <a href=\"/wiki/Hydrogen\">hydrogen</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Helium\">helium</a> with trace amounts of various <a href=\"/wiki/Volatiles\">volatiles</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-guillot_et_al2009-26\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 25;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[25]</span></a></span> This core is similar in composition to the Earth, but more dense. Examination of Saturn's <a href=\"/wiki/Gravitational_moment\">gravitational moment</a>, in combination with physical models of the interior, allowed French astronomers Didier Saumon and Tristan Guillot to place constraints on the mass of Saturn's core. In 2004, they estimated that the core must be 9–22<span>&nbsp;</span>times the mass of the Earth,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-science305_5689_1414-27\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 26;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[26]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-apj609_2_1170-28\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 27;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[27]</span></a></span> which corresponds to a diameter of about 25,000<span>&nbsp;</span>km.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-29\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 28;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[28]</span></a></span> This is surrounded by a thicker liquid <a href=\"/wiki/Metallic_hydrogen\">metallic hydrogen</a> layer, followed by a liquid layer of helium-saturated <a href=\"/wiki/Molecular_hydrogen\">molecular hydrogen</a> that gradually transitions to a gas with increasing altitude. The outermost layer spans 1,000<span>&nbsp;</span>km and consists of gas.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-faure_mensing2007-30\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 29;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[29]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NMM_Saturn-31\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 30;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[30]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-32\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 31;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[31]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Saturn has a hot interior, reaching 11,700<span>&nbsp;</span>°C at its core, and it radiates 2.5 times more energy into space than it receives from the Sun. Jupiter's <a href=\"/wiki/Thermal_energy\">thermal energy</a> is generated by the <a href=\"/wiki/Kelvin–Helmholtz_mechanism\">Kelvin–Helmholtz mechanism</a> of slow <a href=\"/wiki/Gravitational_compression\">gravitational compression</a>, but this alone may not be sufficient to explain heat production for Saturn, because it is less massive. An alternative or additional mechanism may be generation of heat through the \"raining out\" of droplets of helium deep in Saturn's interior. As the droplets descend through the lower-density hydrogen, the process releases heat by <a href=\"/wiki/Friction\">friction</a> and leaves Saturn's outer layers depleted of helium.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-de_pater_lissauer2010-33\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 32;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[32]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-nasa_saturn-34\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 33;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[33]</span></a></span> These descending droplets may have accumulated into a helium shell surrounding the core.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-guillot_et_al2009-26\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 25;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[25]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<div class=\"center\">\n<div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"background:none;border:none;max-width:800px;\">\n<div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div style=\"float: left; margin-top: 0.25em; width: 11px; height: 9.5px;\"><div style=\"position: relative; float: left; width: 0px; height: 0px; -webkit-transform: rotate(360deg); border-style: solid inset;

The head of the storm (bright area) passes the tail circling around the left limb.</figcaption></figure>\n\n<p>Saturn's atmosphere exhibits a banded pattern similar to Jupiter's, but Saturn's bands are much fainter and are much wider near the equator. The nomenclature used to describe these bands is the same as on Jupiter. Saturn's finer cloud patterns were not observed until the flybys of the Voyager spacecraft during the 1980s. Since then, Earth-based <a href=\"/wiki/Telescope\">telescopy</a> has improved to the point where regular observations can be made.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-emp105_2_143-41\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 40;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[40]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>The composition of the clouds varies with depth and increasing pressure. In the upper cloud layers, with the temperature in the range 100–160<span>&nbsp;</span>K and pressures extending between 0.5–2 <a href=\"/wiki/Bar_(unit)\">bar</a>, the clouds consist of ammonia ice. Water <a href=\"/wiki/Ice_cloud\">ice clouds</a> begin at a level where the pressure is about 2.5 bar and extend down to 9.5 bar, where temperatures range from 185–270<span>&nbsp;</span>K. Intermixed in this layer is a band of ammonium hydrosulfide ice, lying in the pressure range 3–6 bar with temperatures of 290–235<span>&nbsp;</span>K. Finally, the lower layers, where pressures are between 10–20 bar and temperatures are 270–330<span>&nbsp;</span>K, contains a region of water droplets with ammonia in aqueous solution.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-dougherty_esposito2009-42\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 41;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[41]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Saturn's usually bland atmosphere occasionally exhibits long-lived ovals and other features common on Jupiter. In 1990, the <a href=\"/wiki/Hubble_Space_Telescope\">Hubble Space Telescope</a> imaged an enormous white cloud near Saturn's equator that was not present during the Voyager encounters and in 1994, another, smaller storm was observed. The 1990 storm was an example of a <a href=\"/wiki/Great_White_Spot\">Great White Spot</a>, a unique but short-lived phenomenon that occurs once every Saturnian year, roughly every 30 Earth years, around the time of the northern hemisphere's <a href=\"/wiki/Summer_solstice\">summer solstice</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-icarus176_1_155-43\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 42;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[42]</span></a></span> Previous Great White Spots were observed in 1876, 1903, 1933 and 1960, with the 1933 storm being the most famous. If the periodicity is maintained, another storm will occur in about 2020.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-44\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 43;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[43]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>The winds on Saturn are the second fastest among the Solar System's planets, after Neptune's. <a href=\"/wiki/Voyager_program\">Voyager</a> data indicate peak easterly winds of 500<span>&nbsp;</span>m/s (1800<span>&nbsp;</span>km/h).<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Voyager_Summary_1-45\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 44;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-te

Most scientists think it is a <a href=\"/wiki/Standing_wave\">standing wave</a> pattern in the atmosphere. Polygonal shapes have been replicated in the laboratory through differ
05-23 18:37:48.616 debug OkHttp "mw-reflink-text\">[76]</span></a></span> While the other <a href=\"/wiki/Gas_giant\">gas giants</a> also have ring systems, Saturn's is the largest and most visible.</p>\n\n<p>There are two main hypotheses regarding the origin of the rings. One hypothesis is that the rings are remnants of a destroyed moon of Saturn. The second hypothesis is that the rings are left over from the original <a href=\"/wiki/Nebula\">nebular</a> material from which Saturn formed. Some ice in the E ring comes from the moon Enceladus's geysers.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Spahn-78\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 77;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[77]</span></a></span> \n<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-79\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 78;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[78]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-80\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 79;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[79]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>In the past, astronomers once thought the rings formed alongside the planet when it formed billions of years ago.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-81\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 80;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[80]</span></a></span> Instead, the age of these planetary rings is probably some hundreds of millions of years.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-82\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 81;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[81]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Beyond the main rings at a distance of 12 million km from the planet is the sparse Phoebe ring, which is tilted at an angle of 27° to the other rings and, like <a href=\"/wiki/Phoebe_(moon)\">Phoebe</a>, orbits in <a href=\"/wiki/Retrograde_motion\">retrograde</a> fashion.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-83\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 82;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[82]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Some of the moons of Saturn, including <a href=\"/wiki/Pandora_(moon)\">Pandora</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Prometheus_(moon)\">Prometheus</a>, act as shepherd moons to confine the rings and prevent them from spreading out.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-russell2004-84\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 83;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[83]</span></a></span> <a href=\"/wiki/Pan_(moon)\">Pan</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Atlas_(moon)\">Atlas</a> cause weak, linear density waves in Saturn's rings that have yielded more reliable calculations of their masses.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-85\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 84;\"><span
