05-23 18:37:48.626 debug OkHttp s of a hurricane at the planet's north pole 20 times larger than those found on Earth, with winds faster than 530<span>&nbsp;</span>km/h.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-141\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 140;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[140]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>On 19 July 2013, \"<a href=\"/wiki/The_Day_the_Earth_Smiled\">The Day the Earth Smiled</a>\", Cassini was pointed towards Earth to capture an image of the <a href=\"/wiki/Earth\">Earth</a> and the <a href=\"/wiki/Moon\">Moon</a> (and, as well, <a href=\"/wiki/Venus\">Venus</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Mars\">Mars</a>) as part of a natural light, multi-image portrait of the entire Saturn system. It was the first time NASA informed the people of Earth that a long-distance photo was being taken in advance.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NYT-20131112-142\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 141;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[141]</span></a></span></p>\n\n","toclevel":3,"line":"Cassini–Huygens spacecraft","anchor":"Cassini.E2.80.93Huygens_spacecraft"},{"id":19,"text":"\n<figure class=\"mw-default-size\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Saturn-27-03-04.jpeg\" class=\"image\"><img src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c0/Saturn-27-03-04.jpeg/220px-Saturn-27-03-04.jpeg\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c0/Saturn-27-03-04.jpeg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c0/Saturn-27-03-04.jpeg/330px-Saturn-27-03-04.jpeg 1.5x\" height=\"140\" width=\"220\"></a><figcaption>Amateur telescopic view</figcaption></figure>\n<figure class=\"mw-default-size\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Saturnoppositions-animated.gif\" class=\"image\"><img src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/fe/Saturnoppositions-animated.gif\" height=\"112\" width=\"175\"></a><figcaption>Simulated appearance of Saturn as seen from Earth at <a href=\"/wiki/Opposition_(astronomy)\" class=\"image\">opposition</a>, 2001-2029</figcaption></figure>\n<p>Saturn is the most distant of the five planets easily visible to the naked eye from Earth, the other four being <a href=\"/wiki/Mercury_(planet)\">Mercury</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Venus\">Venus</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Mars\">Mars</a> and Jupiter. (Uranus and occasionally <a href=\"/wiki/4_Vesta\">4 Vesta</a> are visible to the naked eye in dark skies.) Saturn appears to the naked eye in the night sky as a bright, yellowish point of light with an <a href=\"/wiki/Apparent_magnitude\">apparent magnitude</a> of usually between +1 and 0. It takes approximately 29.5 years for the planet to complete an entire circuit of the <a href=\"/wiki/Ecliptic\">ecliptic</a> against the background constellations of the <a href=\"/wiki/Zodiac\">zodiac</a>. Most people will require an optical aid (very large binoculars or a small telescope) that magnifies at least 30 times to achieve an image of Saturn's rings, in which clear resolution is present.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NMM_Saturn-31\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 30;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[30]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-binoculars-121\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 120;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[120]</span></a></span> Twice every Saturnian year (roughly every 15 Earth years), the rings briefly disappear from view, due to the way in which they are angled and because they are so thin.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-143\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 142;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[142]</span></a></span> Such a \"disappearance\" will next occur in 2025, but Saturn will be too close to the Sun for any ring-crossing observation to be possible.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-144\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 143;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[143]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Saturn and its rings are best seen when the planet is at, or near, <a href=\"/wiki/Opposition_(astronomy)\">opposition</a>, the configuration of a planet when it is at an <a href=\"/wiki/Elongation_(
05-23 18:37:48.626 debug OkHttp astronomy)\">elongation</a> of 180°, and thus appears opposite the Sun in the sky. A Saturnian opposition occurs every year—approximately every 378 days—and results in the planet appearing at its brightest. However, both the Earth and Saturn orbit the Sun on eccentric orbits, which means their distances from the Sun vary over time, and therefore so do their distances from each other, hence varying the brightness of Saturn from one opposition to the other. Also, Saturn appears brighter when the rings are angled such that they are more visible. For example, during the opposition of 17 December 2002, Saturn appeared at its brightest due to a favorable <a href=\"/wiki/File:Saturnoppositions.jpg\">orientation of its rings</a> relative to the Earth,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-opp2002-145\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 144;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[144]</span></a></span> even though Saturn was closer to the Earth and Sun in late 2003.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-opp2002-145\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 144;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[144]</span></a></span></p> \n<figure class=\"mw-default-size\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Saturn_eclipse.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/ba/Saturn_eclipse.jpg/220px-Saturn_eclipse.jpg\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/ba/Saturn_eclipse.jpg/440px-Saturn_eclipse.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/ba/Saturn_eclipse.jpg/330px-Saturn_eclipse.jpg 1.5x\" height=\"108\" width=\"220\"></a><figcaption>Saturn eclipses the Sun, as seen from <a href=\"/wiki/Cassini–Huygens\" class=\"image\">Cassini</a></figcaption></figure>\n<p>Also, from time to time Saturn is <a href=\"/wiki/Occultation\">occulted</a> by the Moon (that is, the Moon covers up Saturn in the sky). As with all the planets in the Solar System, occultations of Saturn occur in “seasons”. Saturnian occultations will take place 12 or more times over a 12-month period, followed by about a five-year period in which no such activity is registered.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Jon-146\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 145;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[145]</span></a></span> Australian astronomy experts Hill and Horner explain the seasonal nature of Saturnian occultations:</p>\n\n<blockquote>This is the result of the fact that the moon’s orbit around the Earth is tilted to the orbit of the Earth around the Sun – and so most of the time, the moon will pass above or below Saturn in the sky, and no occultation will occur. It is only when Saturn lies near the point that the moon’s orbit crosses the “plane of the ecliptic” that occultations can happen – and then they occur every time the moon swings by, until Saturn moves away from the crossing point.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Jon-146\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 145;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[145]</span></a></span></blockquote>\n\n","toclevel":1,"line":"Observation","anchor":"Observation"},{"id":20,"text":"\n<figure class=\"mw-default-size\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Saturn-bonatti.PNG\" class=\"image\"><img src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Saturn-bonatti.PNG/220px-Saturn-bonatti.PNG\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Saturn-bonatti.PNG/440px-Saturn-bonatti.PNG 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Saturn-bonatti.PNG/330px-Saturn-bonatti.PNG 1.5x\" height=\"154\" width=\"220\"></a><figcaption>Saturn, from a 1550 edition of <a href=\"/wiki/Guido_Bonatti\" class=\"image\">Guido Bonatti</a>'s <i>Liber astronomiae</i></figcaption></figure>\n<div class=\"hatnote\">Further information: <a href=\"/wiki/Saturn_in_fiction\">Saturn in fiction</a></div>\n\n<ul><li id=\"mwAdk\"> <a href=\"/wiki/Saturn_(astrology)\">Saturn in astrology</a> (<span><a href=\"/wiki/File:Saturn_symbol.svg\"><img src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/74/Saturn_symbol.svg/22px-Sa

It has the third-largest planetary radius and fourth-largest planetary mass in the <a href=\"/wiki/Solar_System\">Solar System</a>. Uranus is similar in composition to <a href=\"/wiki/Neptune\">Neptune</a>, and both have different bulk chemical composition from that of the larger <a href=\"/wiki/Gas_giant\">gas giants</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Jupiter\">Jupiter</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Saturn\">Saturn</a>. For this reason, scientists often classify Uranus and Neptune as \"<a href=\"/wiki/Ice_giant\">ice giants</a>\" to distinguish them from the gas giants. Uranus's atmosphere is similar to Jupiter's and Saturn's in its primary composition of <a href=\"/wiki/Hydrogen\">hydrogen</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Helium\">helium</a>, but it contains more \"<a href=\"/wiki/Volatiles\">ices</a>\" such as water, <a href=\"/wiki/Ammonia\">ammonia</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Methane\">methane</a>, along with traces of other <a href=\"/wiki/Hydrocarbon\">hydrocarbons</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Lunine_1993-14\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 11;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[11]</span></a></span> It is the coldest planetary <a href=\"/wiki/Atmosphere\">atmosphere</a> in the Solar System, with a minimum temperature of <span>49</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>K (−224.2</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>°C)</span>, and has a complex, layered <a href=\"/wiki/Cloud\">cloud</a> structure with water thought to make up the lowest clouds and methane the uppermost layer of clouds.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Lunine_1993-14\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 11;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[11]</span></a></span> The interior of Uranus is mainly composed of ices and rock.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Podolak_Weizman_et_al._1995-13\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 10;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[10]</span></a></span></p></span><div class=\"hatnote\">This article is about the planet. Like the other <a href=\"/wiki/Giant_planet\">giant planets</a>, Uranus has a <a href=\"/wiki/Rings_of_Uranus\">ring system</a>, a <a href=\"/wiki/Magnetosphere\">magnetosphere</a>, and numerous <a href=\"/wiki/Natural_satellite\">moons</a>. The Uranian system has a unique configuration among those of the planets because its <a href=\"/wiki/Axis_of_rotation\">axis of rotation</a> is tilted sideways, nearly into the plane of its solar orbit. Its north and south poles, therefore, lie where most other planets have their <a href=\"/wiki/Equator\">equators</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Smith_Soderblom_et_al._1986-18\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 15;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[15]</span></a></span> In 1986, images from <a href=\"/wiki/Voyager_2\">Voyager&nbsp;2</a> showed Uranus as an almost featureless planet in visible light, without the cloud bands or storms associated with the other giant planets.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Smith_Soderblom_et_al._1986-18\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 15;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[15]</span></a></span> Observations from Earth have shown seasonal change and increased weather activity as Uranus approached its <a href=\"/wiki/Equinox\">equinox</a> in 2007. Wind speeds can reach 250 metres per second (900<span>&nbsp;</span>km/h, 560<span>&nbsp;</span>mph).<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Sromovsky_.26_Fry_2005-19\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 16;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[16]</span></a></span></p>\n\n"},{"id":1,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"History","line":"History"},{"id":2,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Discovery","line":"Discovery"},{"id":3,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Name","line":"Name"},{"id":4,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Orbit_and_rotation","line":"Orbit and rotation"},{"id":5,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Axial_tilt","line":"Axial tilt"},{"id":6,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Visibility","line":"Visibility"},{"id":7,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Internal_structure","line":"Internal structure"},{"id":8,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Internal_heat","line":"Internal heat"},{"id":9,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Atmosphere","line":"Atmosphere"},{"id":10,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Composition","line":"Composition"},{"id":11,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Troposphere","line":"Troposphere"},{"id":12,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Upper_atmosphere","line":"Upper atmosphere"},{"id":13,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Planetary_rings","line":"Planetary rings"},{"id":14,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Magnetosphere","line":"Magnetosphere"},{"id":15,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Climate","line":"Climate"},{"id":16,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Banded_structure.2C_winds_and_clouds","line":"Banded structure, winds and clouds"},{"id":17,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Seasonal_variation","line":"Seasonal variation"},{"id":18,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Formation","line":"Formation"},{"id":19,"toclevel":1,"an

05-23 18:37:55.577 debug OkHttp {"sections":[{"id":1,"text":"\n<p>Like the five <a href=\"/wiki/Classical_planet\">classical planets</a>, Uranus is visible to the naked eye, but was never recognized as a planet by ancient observers because of its dimness and slow orbit.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-20\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 17;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[17]</span></a></span> Sir <a href=\"/wiki/William_Herschel\">William Herschel</a> announced its discovery on 13 March 1781, expanding the known boundaries of the <a href=\"/wiki/Solar_System\">Solar System</a> for the first time in history and making Uranus the first planet discovered with a <a href=\"/wiki/Telescope\">telescope</a>.</p>\n\n","toclevel":1,"line":"History","anchor":"History"},{"id":2,"text":"\n<figure class=\"mw-default-size mw-halign-left\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:William_Herschel01.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/William_Herschel01.jpg/170px-William_Herschel01.jpg\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/William_Herschel01.jpg/340px-William_Herschel01.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/William_Herschel01.jpg/255px-William_Herschel01.jpg 1.5x\" height=\"208\" width=\"170\"></a><figcaption><a href=\"/wiki/William_Herschel\" class=\"image\">William Herschel</a>, discoverer of Uranus</figcaption></figure>\n\n<p>Uranus had been observed on many occasions before its recognition as a planet, but it was generally mistaken for a star. Possibly the earliest known observation was by <a href=\"/wiki/Hipparchos\">Hipparchos</a>, who in 128 BC may have recorded it as a star for his <a href=\"/wiki/Star_catalogue\">star catalogue</a> that was later incorporated into <a href=\"/wiki/Ptolemy\">Ptolemy</a>'s <a href=\"/wiki/Almagest\">Almagest</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-21\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 18;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[18]</span></a></span> The earliest definite sighting was in 1690 when <a href=\"/wiki/John_Flamsteed\">John Flamsteed</a> observed it at least six times, cataloguing it as 34 <a href=\"/wiki/Taurus_(constellation)\">Tauri</a>. The French astronomer <a href=\"/wiki/Pierre_Lemonnier\">Pierre Lemonnier</a> observed Uranus at least twelve times between 1750 and 1769,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-22\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 19;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[19]</span></a></span> including on four consecutive nights.</p>\n\n<p>Sir <a href=\"/wiki/William_Herschel\">William Herschel</a> observed Uranus on 13 March 1781 from the garden of his house at 19 New King Street in <a href=\"/wiki/Bath,_Somerset\">Bath, Somerset</a>, England (now the <a href=\"/wiki/Herschel_Museum_of_Astronomy\">Herschel Museum of Astronomy</a>),<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-23\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 20;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[20]</span></a></span> and initially reported it (on 26 April 1781) as a <a href=\"/wiki/Comet\">comet</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-24\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 21;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[21]</span></a></span> Herschel \"engaged in a series of observations on the parallax of the fixed stars\",<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Ref-1-25\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 22;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[22]</span></a></span> using a telescope of his own design.</p>\n\n<p>He recorded in his journal \"In the quartile near <a href=\"/wiki/Zeta_Tauri\">ζ Tauri</a><span>&nbsp;</span>... either [a] Nebulous star or perhaps a comet\".<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-26\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 23;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[23]</span></a></span> On 17 March he noted, \"I looked for the Comet or Nebulous Star and found that it is a Comet, for it has changed its place\".<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-27\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 24;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[24]</span></a></span> Whe
05-23 18:37:55.577 debug OkHttp n he presented his discovery to the <a href=\"/wiki/Royal_Society\">Royal Society</a>, he continued to assert that he had found a comet, but also implicitly compared it to a planet:<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Ref-1-25\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 22;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[22]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<blockquote class=\"templatequote\"><i>\"The power I had on when I first saw the comet was 227. From experience I know that the diameters of the fixed stars are not proportionally magnified with higher powers, as planets are; therefore I now put the powers at 460 and 932, and found that the diameter of the comet increased in proportion to the power, as it ought to be, on the supposition of its not being a fixed star, while the diameters of the stars to which I compared it were not increased in the same ratio. Moreover, the comet being magnified much beyond what its light would admit of, appeared hazy and ill-defined with these great powers, while the stars preserved that lustre and distinctness which from many thousand observations I knew they would retain. The sequel has shown that my surmises were well-founded, this proving to be the Comet we have lately observed\"</i>.\n</blockquote>\n\n<figure class=\"mw-default-size mw-halign-left\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:HerschelTelescope.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/HerschelTelescope.jpg/190px-HerschelTelescope.jpg\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/HerschelTelescope.jpg/380px-HerschelTelescope.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/HerschelTelescope.jpg/285px-HerschelTelescope.jpg 1.5x\" height=\"244\" width=\"190\"></a><figcaption>Replica of the telescope used by Herschel to discover Uranus</figcaption></figure>\n\n<p>Herschel notified the <a href=\"/wiki/Astronomer_Royal\">Astronomer Royal</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Nevil_Maskelyne\">Nevil Maskelyne</a>, of his discovery and received this flummoxed reply from him on 23 April: \"I don't know what to call it. It is as likely to be a regular planet moving in an orbit nearly circular to the sun as a Comet moving in a very eccentric ellipsis. I have not yet seen any coma or tail to it\".<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-28\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 25;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[25]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Although Herschel continued to describe his new object as a comet, other astronomers had already begun to suspect otherwise. Finnish-Swedish astronomer <a href=\"/wiki/Anders_Johan_Lexell\">Anders Johan Lexell</a>, working in Russia, was the first to compute the orbit of the new object<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-lexell-29\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 26;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[26]</span></a></span> and its nearly circular orbit led him to a conclusion that it was a planet rather than a comet. Berlin astronomer <a href=\"/wiki/Johann_Elert_Bode\">Johann Elert Bode</a> described Herschel's discovery as \"a moving star that can be deemed a hitherto unknown planet-like object circulating beyond the orbit of Saturn\".<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-30\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 27;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[27]</span></a></span> Bode concluded that its near-circular orbit was more like a planet than a comet.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-31\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 28;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[28]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>The object was soon universally accepted as a new planet. By 1783, Herschel acknowledged this to Royal Society president <a href=\"/wiki/Joseph_Banks\">Joseph Banks</a>: \"By the observation of the most eminent Astronomers in Europe it appears that the new star, which I had the honour of pointing out to them in March 1781, is a Primary Planet of our Solar System.\"<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Dreyer-32\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 29;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\"

It is the fourth-largest planet by diameter and the third-largest by mass. Among the <a href=\"/wiki/Giant_planet\">giant planets</a> in the Solar System, Neptune is the most dense. Neptune is 17 times the mass of <a href=\"/wiki/Earth\">Earth</a> and is slightly more massive than its near-twin <a href=\"/wiki/Uranus\">Uranus</a>, which is 15 times the mass of Earth and slightly larger than Neptune.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-mass2-12\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 3;\" data-mw-group=\"lower-alpha\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[lower-alpha 3]</span></a></span> Neptune orbits the Sun once every 164.8<span>&nbsp;</span><a href=\"/wiki/Julian_year_(astronomy)\">years</a> at an average distance of <span>30.1 </span><a href=\"/wiki/Astronomical_unit\">astronomical unit</a><span>s (4.50</span><span style=\"margin:0 .15em 0 .25em\">×</span><span>10</span><sup about=\"#mwt46\">9</sup><span>&nbsp;</span><span>km)</span>. Named after the <a href=\"/wiki/Neptune_(mythology)\">Roman god of the sea</a>, its <a href=\"/wiki/Astronomical_symbol\">astronomical symbol</a> is ♆, a stylised version of the god Neptune's <a href=\"/wiki/Trident\">trident</a>.</p></span><div class=\"hatnote\">This article is about the planet. 05-23 18:38:03.517 debug OkHttp by <a href=\"/wiki/Empirical_observation\">empirical observation</a>. Unexpected changes in the orbit of Uranus led <a href=\"/wiki/Alexis_Bouvard\">Alexis Bouvard</a> to deduce that its orbit was subject to <a href=\"/wiki/Gravitation\">gravitational</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Perturbation_(astronomy)\">perturbation</a> by an unknown planet. Neptune was subsequently observed with a telescope on 23<span>&nbsp;</span>September 1846<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Hamilton-1\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 1;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[1]</span></a></span> by <a href=\"/wiki/Johann_Galle\">Johann Galle</a> within a <a href=\"/wiki/Degree_(angle)\">degree</a> of the position predicted by <a href=\"/wiki/Urbain_Le_Verrier\">Urbain Le Verrier</a>. Its largest moon, <a href=\"/wiki/Triton_(moon)\">Triton</a>, was discovered shortly thereafter, though none of the planet's remaining known 14 <a href=\"/wiki/Moons_of_Neptune\">moons</a> were located telescopically until the 20th century. The planet's distance from Earth gives it a very small apparent size, making it challenging to study with Earth-based telescopes. Neptune was visited by <i><a href=\"/wiki/Voyager_2\">Voyager 2</a></i>, when it flew by the planet on 25<span>&nbsp;</span>August 1989.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NYT-20141018-KC-13\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 10;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[10]</span></a></span> The advent of <a href=\"/wiki/Hubble_Space_Telescope\">Hubble Space Telescope</a> and large <a href=\"/wiki/Ground-based_telescope\">ground-based telescopes</a> with <a href=\"/wiki/Adaptive_optics\">adaptive optics</a> has recently allowed for additional detailed observations from afar.</p>\n\n<p>Neptune is similar in composition to Uranus, and both have compositions that differ from those of the larger <a href=\"/wiki/Gas_giant\">gas giants</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Jupiter\">Jupiter</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Saturn\">Saturn</a>. Like Jupiter and Saturn, Neptune's atmosphere is composed primarily of <a href=\"/wiki/Hydrogen\">hydrogen</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Helium\">helium</a>, along with traces of <a href=\"/wiki/Hydrocarbon\">hydrocarbons</a> and possibly <a href=\"/wiki/Nitrogen\">nitrogen</a>, but contains a higher proportion of \"ices\" such as water, <a href=\"/wiki/Ammonia\">ammonia</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Methane\">methane</a>. However, its interior, like that of Uranus, is primarily composed of ices and rock,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Podolak_Weizman_et_al._1995-14\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 11;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[11]</span></a></span> and hence Uranus and Neptune are normally considered \"<a href=\"/wiki/Ice_giant\">ice giants</a>\" to emphasise this distinction.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Lunine_1993-15\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 12;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[12]</span></a></span> Traces of methane in the outermost regions in part account for the planet's blue appearance.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-bluecolour-16\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 13;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[13]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>In contrast to the hazy, relatively featureless atmosphere of Uranus, Neptune's atmosphere has active and visible weather patterns. For example, at the time of the <i>Voyager 2</i> <a href=\"/wiki/Planetary_flyby\">flyby</a> in 1989, the planet's southern hemisphere had a <a href=\"/wiki/Great_Dark_Spot\">Great Dark Spot</a> comparable to the <a href=\"/wiki/Great_Red_Spot\">Great Red Spot</a> on Jupiter. These weather patterns are driven by the strongest sustained winds of any planet in the Solar System, with recorded wind speeds as high as <span>2,100 kilometres per hour (580</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>m/s; 1,300</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>mph)</span>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Suomi1991-17\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 14;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[14]</span></a></span> Because of its gre
05-23 18:38:03.517 debug OkHttp at distance from the Sun, Neptune's outer atmosphere is one of the coldest places in the Solar System, with temperatures at its cloud tops approaching <span>55</span><span>&nbsp;</span><a href=\"/wiki/Kelvin\">K</a><span> (−218</span><span>&nbsp;</span><a href=\"/wiki/Celsius\">°C</a><span>)</span>. 05-23 18:38:04.707 debug OkHttp {"sections":[{"id":1,"text":"\n\n","toclevel":1,"line":"History","anchor":"History"},{"id":2,"text":"\n<div class=\"hatnote relarticle mainarticle\">Main article: <a href=\"/wiki/Discovery_of_Neptune\">Discovery of Neptune</a></div>\n\n<p>Some of the earliest recorded observations ever made through a <a href=\"/wiki/Telescope\">telescope</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Galileo_Galilei\">Galileo's</a> drawings on 28 December 1612 and 27 January 1613, contain plotted points that match up with what is now known to be the position of Neptune. On both occasions, Galileo seems to have mistaken Neptune for a <a href=\"/wiki/Fixed_star\">fixed star</a> when it appeared close—in <a href=\"/wiki/Conjunction_(astronomy_and_astrology)\">conjunction</a>—to Jupiter in the <a href=\"/wiki/Night_sky\">night sky</a>;<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-21\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 18;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[18]</span></a></span> hence, he is not credited with Neptune's discovery. At his first observation in December 1612, Neptune was almost stationary in the sky because it had just turned <a href=\"/wiki/Apparent_retrograde_motion\">retrograde</a> that day. This apparent backward motion is created when Earth's orbit takes it past an outer planet. Because Neptune was only beginning its yearly retrograde cycle, the motion of the planet was far too slight to be detected with Galileo's small <a href=\"/wiki/Telescope\">telescope</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-22\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 19;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[19]</span></a></span> In July 2009, <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Melbourne\">University of Melbourne</a> physicist David Jamieson announced new evidence suggesting that Galileo was at least aware that the 'star' he had observed had moved relative to the <a href=\"/wiki/Fixed_stars\">fixed stars</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-23\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 20;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[20]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>In 1821, <a href=\"/wiki/Alexis_Bouvard\">Alexis Bouvard</a> published astronomical tables of the <a href=\"/wiki/Orbit\">orbit</a> of Neptune's neighbour Uranus.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-24\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 21;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[21]</span></a></span> Subsequent observations revealed substantial deviations from the tables, leading Bouvard to hypothesise that an unknown body was <a href=\"/wiki/Perturbation_(astronomy)\">perturbing</a> the orbit through <a href=\"/wiki/Gravitation\">gravitational</a> interaction.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MNRAS7-25\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 22;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[22]</span></a></span> In 1843, <a href=\"/wiki/John_Couch_Adams\">John Couch Adams</a> began work on the orbit of Uranus using the data he had. Via <a href=\"/wiki/Cambridge_Observatory\">Cambridge Observatory</a> director <a href=\"/wiki/James_Challis\">James Challis</a>, he requested extra data from Sir <a href=\"/wiki/George_Biddell_Airy\">George Airy</a>, the <a href=\"/wiki/Astronomer_Royal\">Astronomer Royal</a>, who supplied it in February 1844. Adams continued to work in 1845–46 and produced several different estimates of a new planet.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-26\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 23;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[23]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-27\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 24;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[24]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<figure class=\"mw-default-size mw-halign-left\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Urbain_Le_Verrier.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Urbain_Le_Verrier.jpg/170px-Urbain_Le_Verrier.jpg\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Urbain_Le_Verrier.jpg/340px-Urbain_Le_Verrier.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Urbain_Le_Verrier.jpg/255px-Urbain_Le_Verrier.jpg 1.5x\" heigh

In June 1846, upon seeing Le Verrier's first published estimate of the planet's longitude and its similarity to Adams's estimate, Airy persuaded Challis to search for the planet. Challis vainly scoured the sky throughout August and September.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MNRAS7-25\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 22;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[22]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-28\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 25;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[25]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Meanwhile, Le Verrier by letter urged <a href=\"/wiki/Berlin_Observatory\">Berlin Observatory</a> astronomer <a href=\"/wiki/Johann_Gottfried_Galle\">Johann Gottfried Galle</a> to search with the observatory's <a href=\"/wiki/Refractor\">refractor</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/Heinrich_Louis_d'Arrest\">Heinrich d'Arrest</a>, a student at the observatory, suggested to Galle that they could compare a recently drawn chart of the sky in the region of Le Verrier's predicted location with the current sky to seek the displacement characteristic of a <a href=\"/wiki/Planet\">planet</a>, as opposed to a fixed star. On the evening of 23<span>&nbsp;</span>September 1846, the day Galle received the letter, he discovered Neptune within 1° of where Le Verrier had predicted it to be, about 12° from Adams' prediction. Challis later realised that he had observed the planet twice, on 4 and 12<span>&nbsp;</span>August, but did not recognise it as a planet because he lacked an up-to-date star map and was distracted by his concurrent work on comet observations.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MNRAS7-25\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 22;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[22]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-29\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 26;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[26]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>In the wake of the discovery, there was much nationalistic rivalry between the French and the British over who deserved credit for the discovery. Eventually, an international consensus emerged that both Le Verrier and Adams jointly deserved credit. Since 1966, <a href=\"/wiki/Dennis_Rawlins\">Dennis Rawlins</a> has questioned the credibility of Adams's claim to co-discovery, and the issue was re-evaluated by historians with the return in 1998 of the \"Neptune papers\" (historical documents) to the <a href=\"/wiki/Royal_Observatory,_Greenwich\">Royal Observatory, Greenwich</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Neptdisc-30\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 27;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[27]</span></a></span> After reviewing the documents, they suggest that \"Adams does not deserve equal credit with Le Verrier for the discovery of Neptune. That credit belongs only to the person who succeeded both in predicting the planet's place and in convincing astronomers to search for it.\"<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-31\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 28;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[28]</span></a></span></p>\n\n","toclevel":2,"line":"Discovery","anchor":"Discovery"},{"id":3,"text":"\n<p>Shortly after its discovery, Neptune was referred to simply as \"the planet exterior to Uranus\" or as \"Le Verrier's planet\". The first suggestion for a name came from Galle, who proposed the name <i><a href=\"/wiki/Janus_(mythology)\">Janus</a></i>. In England, Challis put forward the name <i><a href=\"/wiki/Oceanus\">Oceanus</a></i>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-32\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 29;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[29]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Claiming the right to name his discovery, Le Verrier quickly proposed the name <i>Neptu

This suggestion met with stiff resistance outside France.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-34\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 31;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[31]</span></a></span> French almanacs quickly reintroduced the name <i>Herschel</i> for <i>Uranus</i>, after that planet's discoverer Sir <a href=\"/wiki/William_Herschel\">William Herschel</a>, and <i>Leverrier</i> for the new planet.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-35\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 32;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[32]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/Friedrich_Georg_Wilhelm_von_Struve\">Struve</a> came out in favour of the name <i>Neptune</i> on 29<span>&nbsp;</span>December 1846, to the <a href=\"/wiki/Russian_Academy_of_Sciences\">Saint Petersburg Academy of Sciences</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-36\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 33;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[33]</span></a></span> Soon, <i>Neptune</i> became the internationally accepted name. In <a href=\"/wiki/Roman_mythology\">Roman mythology</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Neptune_(mythology)\">Neptune</a> was the god of the sea, identified with the Greek <a href=\"/wiki/Poseidon\">Poseidon</a>. The demand for a mythological name seemed to be in keeping with the nomenclature of the other planets, all of which, except for Earth, were named for deities in <a href=\"/wiki/Greek_mythology\">Greek</a> and Roman mythology.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-USGS-37\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 34;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[34]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Most languages today, even in countries that have no direct link to Greco-Roman culture, use some variant of the name \"Neptune\" for the planet. However, in Chinese, Japanese, and <a href=\"/wiki/Korean_language\">Korean</a>, the planet's name was translated as \"sea king star\" (<span>海王星</span>), because Neptune was the god of the sea.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-38\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 35;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[35]</span></a></span> In <a href=\"/wiki/Mongolian_language\">Mongolian</a>, Neptune is called <i>Dalain Van</i> (Далайн ван), reflecting its namesake god's role as the ruler of the sea. In modern <a href=\"/wiki/Greek_language\">Greek</a> the planet is called <i>Poseidon</i> (Ποσειδώνας, <i>Poseidonas</i>), the Greek counterpart of Neptune.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-39\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 36;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[36]</span></a></span> In <a href=\"/wiki/Hebrew_language\">Hebrew</a>, \"Rahab\" (רהב), from <a href=\"/wiki/Rahab_(Egypt)#Jewish_folklore\">a Biblical sea monster</a> mentioned in the <a href=\"/wiki/Book_of_Psalms\">Book of Psalms</a>, was selected in a vote managed by the <a href=\"/wiki/Academy_of_the_Hebrew_Language\">Academy of the Hebrew Language</a> in 2009 as the official name for the planet, even though the existing Latin term \"Neptun\" (נפטון) is commonly used.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Haaretz-40\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 37;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[37]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Hayadan.org.il-41\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 38;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[38]</span></a></span> In <a href=\"/wiki/Māori_language\">Māori</a>, the planet is called <i>Tangaroa</i>, named after the <a href=\"/wiki/Tangaroa\">Māori god of the sea</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-42\" style=\"count

In particular, it seems that the <i>Liberté</i> arc might disappear in as little as one century.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-79\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 75;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[75]</span></a></span></p>\n\n","toclevel":1,"line":"Planetary rings","anchor":"Planetary_rings"},{"id":10,"text":"\n<figure class=\"mw-default-size\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Neptune_storms.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Neptune_storms.jpg/220px-Neptune_storms.jpg\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Neptune_storms.jpg/440px-Neptune_storms.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Neptune_storms.jpg/330px-Neptune_storms.jpg 1.5x\" height=\"203\" width=\"220\"></a><figcaption>The <a href=\"/wiki/Great_Dark_Spot\" class=\"image\">Great Dark Spot</a> (top), Scooter (middle white cloud),<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-scooter-80\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 76;\" class=\"image\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[76]</span></a></span> and the <a href=\"/wiki/Small_Dark_Spot\" class=\"image\">Small Dark Spot</a> (bottom), with contrast exaggerated.</figcaption></figure>\n\n<p>Neptune's weather is characterised by extremely dynamic storm systems, with winds reaching speeds of almost <span>600</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>m/s (2,200</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>km/h; 1,300</span><span>&nbsp;</span><

This is interpreted as evidence for upwelling at the equator and subsidence near the poles.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Lunine_1993-15\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 12;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[12]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>In 2007, it was discovered that the upper troposphere of Neptune's south pole was about 10 K warmer than the rest of its atmosphere, which averages approximately <span>73</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>K (−200</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>°C)</span>. The temperature differential is enough to let methane, which elsewhere is frozen in the troposphere, escape into the stratosphere near the pole.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-84\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 80;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[80]</span></a></span> The relative \"hot spot\" is due to Neptune's <a href=\"/wiki/Axial_tilt\">axial tilt</a>, which has exposed the south pole to the <a href=\"/wiki/Sun\">Sun</a> for the last quarter of Neptune's year, or roughly 40 Earth years. As Neptune slowly moves towards the opposite side of the Sun, the south pole will be darkened and the north pole illuminated, causing the methane release to shift to the north pole.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-85\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 81;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[81]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Because of seasonal changes, the cloud bands in the southern hemisphere of Neptune have been observed to increase in size and <a href=\"/wiki/Albedo\">albedo</a>. The storm resembled the <a href=\"/wiki/Great_Red_Spot\">Great Red Spot</a> of Jupiter. Some five years later, on 2<span>&nbsp;</span>November 1994, the <a href=\"/wiki/Hubble_Space_Telescope\">Hubble Space Telescope</a> did not see the Great Dark Spot on the planet. Instead, a new storm similar to the Great Dark Spot was found in the planet's northern hemisphere.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-87\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 83;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[83]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>The Scooter is another storm, a white cloud group farther south than the Great Dark Spot. It was initially completely dark, but as <i>Voyager 2</i> approached the planet, a bright core developed and can be seen in most of the highest-resolution images.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-88\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 84;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[84]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Neptune's dark spots are thought to occur in the <a href=\"/wiki/Troposphere\">troposphere</a> at lower altitudes than the brighter cloud features,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-89\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 85;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[85]</span></a></span> so they appear as holes in the upper cloud decks. He is the <a href=\"/wiki/List_of_African-American_firsts\">first</a> <a href=\"/wiki/African_American\">African American</a> to hold the office, as well as the first president born outside of the <a href=\"/wiki/Contiguous_United_States\">continental United States</a>. Born in <a href=\"/wiki/Honolulu\">Honolulu</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Hawaii\">Hawaii</a>, Obama is a graduate of <a href=\"/wiki/Columbia_University\">Columbia University</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Harvard_Law_School\">Harvard Law School</a>, where he served as president of the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Harvard_Law_Review\">Harvard Law Review</a></i>. He was a <a href=\"/wiki/Community_organizing\">community organizer</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Chicago\">Chicago</a> before earning his <a href=\"/wiki/Juris_Doctor\">law degree</a>. He worked as a <a href=\"/wiki/Civil_and_political_rights\">civil rights</a> attorney and taught <a href=\"/wiki/Constitutional_law\">constitutional law</a> at <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Chicago_Law_School\">University of Chicago Law School</a> between 1992 and 2004. He began his presidential campaign in 2007 and, after <a href=\"/wiki/Barack_Obama_presidential_primary_campaign,_2008\">a close primary campaign</a> against <a href=\"/wiki/Hillary_Clinton\">Hillary Rodham Clinton</a> in 2008, he won sufficient delegates in the <a href=\"/wiki/Democratic_Party_presidential_primaries,_2008\">Democratic Party p

He then defeated <a href=\"/wiki/Republican_Party_(United_States)\">Republican</a> nominee <a href=\"/wiki/John_McCain\">John McCain</a> in the <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_presidential_election,_2008\">general election</a>, and was <a href=\"/wiki/First_inauguration_of_Barack_Obama\">inaugurated as president</a> on January 20, 2009. Nine months after his inauguration, Obama was named the <a href=\"/wiki/2009_Nobel_Peace_Prize\">2009 Nobel Peace Prize</a> laureate.</p>\n\n<p>During his first two years in office, Obama signed into law <a href=\"/wiki/Stimulus_(economics)\">economic stimulus</a> legislation in response to the <a href=\"/wiki/Great_Recession\">Great Recession</a> in the form of the <a href=\"/wiki/American_Recovery_and_Reinvestment_Act_of_2009\">American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009</a> and the <a href=\"/wiki/Tax_Relief,_Unemployment_Insurance_Reauthorization,_and_Job_Creation_Act_of_2010\">Tax Relief, Unemployment Insurance Reauthorization, and Job Creation Act of 2010</a>. Other major domestic initiatives in his first term included the <a href=\"/wiki/Patient_Protection_and_Affordable_Care_Act\">Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act</a>, often referred to as \"Obamacare\"; the <a href=\"/wiki/Dodd–Frank_Wall_Street_Reform_and_Consumer_Protection_Act\">Dodd–Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act</a>; and the <a href=\"/wiki/Don't_Ask,_Don't_Tell_Repeal_Act_of_2010\">Don't Ask, Don't Tell Repeal Act of 2010</a>. In foreign policy, Obama <a href=\"/wiki/Withdrawal_of_U.S._troops_from_Iraq\">ended U.S. military involvement</a> in the <a href=\"/wiki/Iraq_War\">Iraq War</a>, increased U.S. troop levels in <a href=\"/wiki/War_in_Afghanistan_(2001–present)\">Afghanistan</a>, signed the <a href=\"/wiki/New_START\">New START</a> arms control treaty with <a href=\"/wiki/Russia\">Russia</a>, ordered <a href=\"/wiki/2011_military_intervention_in_Libya\">U.S. military involvement in Libya</a> in opposition to <a href=\"/wiki/Muammar_Gaddafi\">Muammar Gaddafi</a>, and ordered the military operation that resulted in the <a href=\"/wiki/Death_of_Osama_bin_Laden\">death of Osama bin Laden</a>. In January 2011, <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_midterm_elections,_2010\">the Republicans regained control of the House of Representatives</a> as the Democratic Party lost a total of 63 seats; and, after a lengthy debate over federal spending and whether or not to raise the nation's <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_debt_ceiling\">debt limit</a>, Obama signed the <a href=\"/wiki/Budget_Control_Act_of_2011\">Budget Control Act of 2011</a> and the <a href=\"/wiki/American_Taxpayer_Relief_Act_of_2012\">American Taxpayer Relief Act of 2012</a>.</p>\n\n<p>Obama was <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_presidential_election,_2012\">reelected president</a> in November 2012, defeating Republican nominee <a href=\"/wiki/Mitt_Romney\">Mitt Romney</a>, and was <a href=\"/wiki/Second_inauguration_of_Barack_Obama\">sworn in for a second term</a> on January 20, 2013. During his second term, Obama has promoted domestic policies related to <a href=\"/wiki/Gun_politics_in_the_United_States\">gun control</a> in response to the <a href=\"/wiki/Sandy_Hook_Elementary_School_shooting\">Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting</a>, and has called for greater inclusiveness for <a href=\"/wiki/LGBT_Americans\">LGBT Americans</a>, while his administration has filed briefs which urged the <a href=\"/wiki/Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States\">Supreme Court</a> to strike down part of the federal <a href=\"/wiki/Defense_of_Marriage_Act\">Defense of Marriage Act</a> and state level <a href=\"/wiki/Same-sex_marriage_in_the_United_States\">same-sex marriage</a> bans as unconstitutional. In foreign policy, Obama ordered <a href=\"/wiki/American-led_intervention_in_Iraq_(2014–present)\">U.S. military intervention in Iraq</a> in response to <a href=\"/wiki/Iraqi_insurgency_(2011–present)\">gains made</a> by

There are several hypotheses for its origin; the most widely accepted explanation is that the Moon formed from the debris left over after a <a href=\"/wiki/Giant_impact_hypothesis\">giant impact</a> between Earth and a <a href=\"/wiki/Mars\">Mars</a>-sized body called <a href=\"/wiki/Theia_(planet)\">Theia</a>.</p>\n\n<p>The Moon is in <a href=\"/wiki/Synchronous_rotation\">synchronous rotation</a> with Earth, always showing the same face with its <a href=\"/wiki/Near_side_of_the_Moon\">near side</a> marked by dark volcanic <a href=\"/wiki/Lunar_mare\">maria</a> that fill between the bright ancient crustal highlands and the prominent <a href=\"/wiki/Impact_crater\">impact craters</a>. It is the second-brightest regularly visible <a href=\"/wiki/Celestial_object\">celestial object</a> in Earth's sky after the <a href=\"/wiki/Sun\">Sun</a>, as measured by <a href=\"/wiki/Illuminance\">illuminance</a> on Earth's surface. Its surface is actually dark (although it can appear a <a href=\"/wiki/Moonlight\">very bright white</a>) with a <a href=\"/wiki/Reflectance\">reflectance</a> just slightly higher than that of worn <a href=\"/wiki/Asphalt_concrete\">asphalt</a>. Its prominence in the sky and its regular cycle of <a href=\"/wiki/Lunar_phases\">phases</a> have made the Moon an important <a href=\"/wiki/Culture\">cultural</a> influence since <a href=\"/wiki/Ancient_history\">ancient</a> times on <a href=\"/wiki/Moon#Name_and_etymology\">language</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Lunar_calendar\">calendars</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Moon_in_fiction\">art</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Lunar_deity\">mythology</a>.</p>\n\n<p>The Moon's gravitational influence produces the <a href=\"/wiki/Ocean_tides\">ocean tides</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Earth_tide\">body tides</a>, and the <a href=\"/wiki/Tidal_acceleration\">slight lengthening</a> of the day. The Moon's current orbital distance is about thirty times the diameter of Earth, with its <a href=\"/wiki/Angular_diameter\">apparent size</a> in the sky almost the same as that of the Sun, resulting in th
05-23 18:38:20.918 debug OkHttp e Moon covering the Sun nearly precisely in total <a href=\"/wiki/Solar_eclipse\">solar eclipse</a>. This matching of apparent visual size will not continue in the far future. The Moon's linear distance from Earth is currently increasing at a rate of <span>3.82</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>±</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>0.07 centimetres (1.504</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>±</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>0.028</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>in)</span> per year, but this rate is not constant.</p>\n\n<p>The <a href=\"/wiki/Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</a>'s <a href=\"/wiki/Luna_programme\">Luna programme</a> was the first to reach the Moon with <a href=\"/wiki/Unmanned_spacecraft\">unmanned spacecraft</a> in 1959; the <a href=\"/wiki/United_States\">United States</a>' <a href=\"/wiki/NASA\">NASA</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Apollo_program\">Apollo program</a> achieved the only manned missions to date, beginning with the first manned lunar orbiting mission by <a href=\"/wiki/Apollo_8\">Apollo 8</a> in 1968, and six manned lunar landings between 1969 and 1972, with the first being <a href=\"/wiki/Apollo_11\">Apollo 11</a>. These missions returned over <span>380</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>kg (840</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>lb)</span> of <a href=\"/wiki/Moon_rock\">lunar rocks</a>, which have been used to develop a <a href=\"/wiki/Geology\">geological</a> understanding of the Moon's origin, the formation of <a href=\"/wiki/Internal_structure_of_the_Moon\">its internal structure</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Geology_of_the_Moon\">its subsequent history</a>. After the <a href=\"/wiki/Apollo_17\">Apollo 17</a> mission in 1972, the Moon has been visited only by unmanned spacecraft.</p>\n\n"},{"id":1,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Name_and_etymology","line":"Name class=\"hatnote\">See also: <a href=\"/wiki/List_of_lunar_deities\">list of lunar deities</a></div>\n\n<p>The usual English <a href=\"/wiki/Proper_name\">proper name</a> for Earth's natural satellite is \"the Moon\".<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-15\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 10;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[10]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-PN-FAQ-16\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 11;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[11]</span></a></span> The noun <i>moon</i> is derived from <i>moone</i> (around 1380), which developed from <i>mone</i> (1135), which is derived from <a href=\"/wiki/Old_English\">Old English</a> <i>mōna</i> (dating from before 725), which ultimately stems from <a href=\"/wiki/Proto-Germanic\">Proto-Germanic</a> <i>*mǣnōn</i>, like all <a href=\"/wiki/Germanic_languages\">Germanic language</a> cognates.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-barnhart1995-17\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 12;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[12]</span></a></span> Occasionally, the name \"Luna\" is used, such as for a personified Moon in poetry or to distinguish it from other moons in science fiction.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-18\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 13;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[13]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>The principal modern English adjective pertaining to the Moon is <i>lunar</i>, derived from the Latin <i>Luna</i>. A less common adjective is <i>selenic</i>, derived from the Ancient Greek <i><a href=\"/wiki/Selene\">Selene</a></i> (<span><i>Σελήνη</i></span>), from which is derived the prefix \"seleno-\" (as in <i><a href=\"/wiki/Selenography\">selenography</a></i>).<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-oed-19\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 14;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[14]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-20\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 15;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[15]</span></a></span> Both the Greek Selene and the Roman goddess <a href=\"/wiki/Diana_(mythology)\">Diana</a> were alternatively called <a href=\"/wiki/Cynthia\">Cynthia</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Pannen2010-21\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 16;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[16]</span></a></span> The names Luna, Cynthia, and Selene are reflected in terminology for <a href=\"/wiki/Lunar_orbit\">lunar orbits</a> in words such as <i>apolune</i>, <i>pericynthion</i>, and <i>selenocentric</i>. etymology","anchor":"Name_and_etymology"},{"id":2,"text":"\n<div class=\"hatnote relarticle mainarticle\">Main articles: <a href=\"/wiki/Origin_of_the_Moon\">Origin of the Moon</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Giant_impact_hypothesis\">Giant impact hypothesis</a></div>\n\n<p>Several mechanisms have been proposed for the Moon's formation <span class=\"nowrap\">4.527 ± 0.010 billion</span> years ago,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-age-22\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 6;\" data-mw-group=\"lower-alpha\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[lower-alpha 6]</span></a></span> some 30–50 million years after the origin of the Solar System.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-23\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 17;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[17]</span></a></span> Recent research presented by Rick Carlson indicates a slightly lower age of between 4.40 and 4.45 billion years.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-24\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 18;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[18]</span></a></span>\n<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-25\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 19;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[19]</span></a></span> These mechanisms included the fission of the Moon from Earth's crust through <a href=
05-23 18:38:21.958 debug OkHttp \"/wiki/Centrifugal_force\">centrifugal force</a><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Binder-26\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 20;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[20]</span></a></span> (which would require too great an initial spin of Earth),<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-BotM-27\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 21;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[21]</span></a></span> the gravitational capture of a pre-formed Moon<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Mitler-28\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 22;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[22]</span></a></span> (which would require an unfeasibly extended <a href=\"/wiki/Earth's_atmosphere\">atmosphere of Earth</a> to <a href=\"/wiki/Dissipation\">dissipate</a> the energy of the passing Moon),<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-BotM-27\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 21;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[21]</span></a></span> and the co-formation of Earth and the Moon together in the primordial <a href=\"/wiki/Accretion_disk\">accretion disk</a> (which does not explain the depletion of metals in the Moon).<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-BotM-27\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 21;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[21]</span></a></span> These hypotheses also cannot account for the high <a href=\"/wiki/Angular_momentum\">angular momentum</a> of the Earth–Moon system.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-29\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 23;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[23]</span></a></span></p>\n<figure class=\"mw-halign-right\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Evolution_of_the_Moon.ogv\" class=\"image\"><img src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/df/Evolution_of_the_Moon.ogv/250px--Evolution_of_the_Moon.ogv.jpg\" //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/df/Evolution_of_the_Moon.ogv/375px--Evolution_of_the_Moon.ogv.jpg 1.5x\" height=\"141\" width=\"250\"></a><figcaption>The evolution of the Moon and a tour of the Moon</figcaption></figure>\n<p>The prevailing hypothesis today is that the Earth–Moon system formed as a result of a <a href=\"/wiki/Giant_impact_hypothesis\">giant impact</a>, where a <a href=\"/wiki/Mars\">Mars</a>-sized body (named <i><a href=\"/wiki/Theia_(planet)\">Theia</a></i>) collided with the newly formed <a href=\"/wiki/History_of_the_Earth\">proto-Earth</a>, blasting material into orbit around it that accreted to form the Moon.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-taylor1998-30\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 24;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[24]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-31\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 25;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[25]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>This <a href=\"/wiki/Hypothesis\">hypothesis</a> perhaps best explains the evidence, although not perfectly. Eighteen months prior to an October 1984 conference on lunar origins, Bill Hartmann, Roger Phillips, and Jeff Taylor challenged fellow lunar scientists: \"You have eighteen months. Go back to your Apollo data, go back to your computer, do whatever you have to, but make up your mind. Don't come to our conference unless you have something to say about the Moon's birth.\" At the 1984 conference at Kona, Hawaii, the giant impact hypothesis emerged as the most popular. </p><blockquote>Before the conference, there were partisans of the three \"traditional\" theories, plus a few people who were starting to take the giant impact seriously, and there was a huge apathetic middle who didn’t think the debate would ever be resolved. Afterward there were essentially only two groups: the giant impact camp and the agnostics.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Dana-Mackenzie's-book-32\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 26;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[26]</span></a></span></blockquote>\n\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/Late_Heavy_Bombardment\">Giant impacts</a
05-23 18:38:21.958 debug OkHttp > are thought to have been common in the early Solar System. Computer simulations modelling a giant impact are consistent with measurements of the angular momentum of the Earth–Moon system and the small size of the lunar core. These simulations also show that most of the Moon came from the impactor, not from the proto-Earth.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-33\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 27;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[27]</span></a></span> However, more-recent tests suggest more of the Moon coalesced from Earth and not the impactor.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-34\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 28;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[28]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-35\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 29;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[29]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-36\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 30;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[30]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-37\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 31;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[31]</span></a></span> <a href=\"/wiki/Meteorite\">Meteorites</a> show that other inner Solar System bodies such as <a href=\"/wiki/Mars\">Mars</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Vesta_(asteroid)\">Vesta</a> have very different oxygen and tungsten <a href=\"/wiki/Isotope\">isotopic</a> compositions to Earth, whereas Earth and the Moon have nearly identical isotopic compositions. Post-impact mixing of the vaporized material between the forming Earth and Moon could have equalized their isotopic compositions,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Pahlevan2007-38\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 32;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[32]</span></a></span> although this is debated.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-39\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 33;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[33]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>The large amount of energy released in the giant impact event and the subsequent re-accretion of material in Earth orbit would have melted the outer shell of Earth, forming a magma ocean.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Warren1985-40\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 34;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[34]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-41\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 35;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[35]</span></a></span> The newly formed Moon would also have had its own <a href=\"/wiki/Lunar_magma_ocean\">lunar magma ocean</a>; estimates for its depth range from about <span>500</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>km (300 miles)</span> to the entire radius of the Moon (<span>1,737</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>km (1,079 miles)</span>).<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Warren1985-40\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 34;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[34]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Despite its accuracy in explaining many lines of evidence, there are still some difficulties that are not fully explained by the giant impact hypothesis, most of them involving the Moon's composition.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-42\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 36;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[36]</span></a></span></p>\n<div class=\"thumb tmulti tnone center\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:591px;max-width:591px\"><div style=\"clear:both;font-weight:bold;text-align:center;background-color:transparent\"><a href=\"/wiki/Oceanus_Procellarum\">Oceanus Procellarum</a> (\"Ocean of Storms\")</div><div class=\"tsingle\" style=\"float:left;margin:1px;width:291px;max-width:291px\"><div class=\"thumbimage\" style=\"height:107px;overflow:hidden\"><span><a href=\"/wiki/File:14-236-LunarGrailMission-OceanusProcellarum-Rifts-Overall-20141001.jpg\"><img src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/14-236-LunarGrailMission-OceanusProcellarum-Rifts-Overall-20141001.jpg/289px-14-236-LunarGrailMission-OceanusProcellarum-Rifts-Overall-20141001.jpg\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wik
